ysia)|Minister of Agricultue and Agro-based Industry]]\n| term_start3 = 19 March 2008\n| primeminister3 = [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]\n| monarch3 = Mizan Zainal Abidin\n| term_end3 = 9 April 2009\n| predecessor3 = [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]\n| successor3 = [[Noh Omar]]\n| deputy3 = [[Rohani Abdul Karim]]\n| constituency3 = Jeli\n| office2 = [[Minister of International Trade and Industry (Malaysia)|Minister of International Trade and Industry]]\n| term_start2 = 10 April 2009\n| term_end2 = 10 May 2018\n| alongside2 = [[Ong Ka Chuan]] (2015\u20132018)\n| primeminister2 = [[Najib Razak]]\n| deputy2 = 1. [[Mukhriz Mahathir]] (2009\u20132013)<br />2. [[Jacob Dungau Sagan]] (2009\u20132013)<br />3. [[Hamim Samuri]] (2013\u20132015)<br />4. [[Lee Chee Leong]] (2014\u20132016)<br />5. [[Ahmad Maslan]] (2015\u20132018)<br /> 6. [[Chua Tee Yong]] (2016\u20132018)\n| predecessor2 = [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]\n| successor2 = [[Darell Leiking|Ignatius Dorell Leiking]]\n| constituency2 = [[Jeli (federal constituency)|Jeli]]\n| monarch2 = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />[[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Abdul Halim]]<br />[[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]\n| office8 = Chair of the [[Budget Select Committee (Malaysia)|Budget Select Committee]]\n| term_start8 = 4 December 2018\n| term_end8 = 10 March 2020\n| predecessor8 = ''Office established''\n| successor8 = \n| constituency_MP9 = [[Jeli (federal constituency)|Jeli]]\n| parliament9 = Malaysian\n| majority9 = 7,353 ([[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]])<br />4,436 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])<br />5,336 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br />6,647 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| term_start9 = 21 March 2004\n| term_end9 = \n| predecessor9 = Mohd Apandi Mohamad\n| successor9 =\n| term_start10 = 7 June 1995\n| term_end10 = 29 November 1999 \n| predecessor10 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor10 = Mohd Apandi Mohamad\n| majority10 = 572 ([[1995 Malaysian general election|1995]])\n| constituency_AM11 = [[Air Lanas (state constituency)|Air Lanas]]\n| assembly11 = Kelantan State Legislative\n| term_start11 = 6 May 2013\n| term_end11 = \n| majority11 = 47 (2013)<br />359 ([[2018 Kelantan state election|2018]])\n| predecessor11 = Abdullah Ya'kub\n| successor11 = \n| term_start12 = 21 March 2004\n| predecessor12 = Abdullah Ya'kub\n| majority12 = 799 (2004)\n| term_end12 = 8 March 2008\n| successor12 = Abdullah Ya'kub\n| birth_name = Mustapa bin Mohamed\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1950|9|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Bachok]], [[Kelantan]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n| residence = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]] (1978\u20132018)<br />[[Malaysian United Indigenous Party|BERSATU]] (2018\u2013present)\n| otherparty = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Melbourne]]<br />[[Boston University]]\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| relations = \n| spouse = Khamarzan Ahmad Meah\n| children = 4\n| website = \n| footnotes = {{pom|3551}}\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Dato' Sri|Dato' Sri]] '''Mustapa bin Mohamed''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0645\u0635\u0637\u0641\u0649 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f; born 25 September 1950), commonly known as ''Tok Pa'' among local Kelantanese,<ref>{{cite web|title=Tok Pa, a man of the people|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/06/27/datuk-pa-a-man-of-the-people/|website=Free Malaysia Today|accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> is a [[Malaysians|Malaysian]] politician, and currently serving as [[Minister of Economic Affairs (Malaysia)|Minister of Economic Affairs]] since 10 March 2020. He is the incumbent [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] (MP) of Malaysia for the seat of [[Jeli]] in [[Kelantan]], representing the [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party]] (BERSATU), a component of [[Perikatan Nasional]] (PN) coalition. He became a BERSATU member following his decision to quit [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) on 18 September 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/09/18/tok-pa-quits-umno/|title=Tok Pa quits Umno, disagrees with party's direction (updated) - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMustapa is an economist.<ref name=\"Taipei\"/> He graduated from the [[University of Melbourne]], Australia, with a First Class Honours degree in Economics and from [[Boston University]] with a Masters in Economic Development.<ref>{{cite news|title=The top corporate figures|date=23 May 2004|work=[[New Straits Times]]|publisher=[[New Straits Times Press]]}}</ref>\n\nHe is married to Khamarzan Ahmad Meah and the couple has four children.\n\n==Political career==\nMustapa was elected to Parliament in the [[1995 Malaysian general election|1995 election]] for Jeli constituency, but was defeated for re-election in [[1999 Malaysian general election|1999]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com.au/newspapers?id=LNIVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iBQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5919,6808&dq=jeli+and+mustapa+and+1995&hl=en|title=Next Bank Negara governor: Mustapa on the list|last=Shamsul Akmar|date=19 April 2000|work=[[New Straits Times]]|publisher=[[New Straits Times Press]]|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> He won back the seat in the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]]. In 2004 he was also elected to the [[Kelantan State Legislative Assembly]] for the Air Lanas seat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2004/3/28/nation/7643528&sec=nation|title=Cabinet-level boost for the east coast|last=Tan|first=Joceline|date=28 March 2004|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=27 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622031448/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2004%2F3%2F28%2Fnation%2F7643528&sec=nation|archivedate=22 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He had been slated to become [[Menteri Besar|Chief Minister]] of Kelantan but BN failed to win a majority in the state Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2004/3/24/nation/7607244&sec=nation|title=Promise of balanced and sensible govt|last=Wong Chun Wai|date=24 March 2004|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=27 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622031503/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2004%2F3%2F24%2Fnation%2F7607244&sec=nation|archivedate=22 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was re-elected in [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 election]]. In [[2013 Malaysian general election|2004 election]], he retained his parliamentary seat and again won the state seat of Air Lanas concurrently but with a slim 47 votes.\n\nMustapa was the former Minister for International Trade and Industry in the BN federal government. Previously, he has also held a number of other government portfolios, including Deputy Finance Minister,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com.au/newspapers?id=Z5cWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qBMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6716,1252638&dq=mustapa+mohamed&hl=en|title=Wooing the voters in Kelantan|last=Tan|first=Joceline|author2=Hisham Mahzan|date=5 March 2005|work=[[New Straits Times]]|publisher=[[New Straits Times Press]]|accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref> Minister for Entrepreneur Development,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com.au/newspapers?id=AIM0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=HhUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1712,1781447&dq=mustapa+mohamed&hl=en|title=Cabbies undergo front-liners course|date=29 May 1997|work=[[New Straits Times]]|publisher=[[New Straits Times Press]]|accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref> Minister in the Prime Minister's Department,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?click_id=126&art_id=qw1080398520797B254&set_id=1|title=Badawi keeps his friends close in new cabinet|last=Lau Y-Sing|date=27 March 2004|work=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref> Minister for Higher Education,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/education/story.asp?file=/2007/12/9/education/19680993&sec=education|title=Enhancing ties with Iran|last=Tan Shiow Chin|date=9 December 2007|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=26 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622031125/http://thestar.com.my/education/story.asp?file=%2F2007%2F12%2F9%2Feducation%2F19680993&sec=education|archivedate=22 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Minister for Agriculture and Agro-based Industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2008/3/25/nation/20737949&sec=nation|title=Slashing food imports is new Agriculture Minister's priority|date=25 March 2008|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=26 May 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622031256/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F3%2F25%2Fnation%2F20737949&sec=nation|archivedate=22 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was appointed to the Trade portfolio when [[Najib Razak]] became [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Prime Minister]] in April 2009.<ref name=\"Taipei\">{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2009/04/10/2003440636|title=New Malaysian prime minister unveils Cabinet|date=10 April 2009|work=[[Taipei Times]]|accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of BN's loss in the 2018 election and UMNO's own party election, Mustapa announced on 18 September 2018 that he has quit UMNO, citing disagreements with the party's current direction.<ref name=\":0\" /> On the 27 October 2018, Mustapa joined [[Malaysian United Indigenous Party|BERSATU]].\n\nOn 4 December 2018, Mustapa was elected chair of the [[Budget Select Committee (Malaysia)|Budget Select Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/454684|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=26 April 2019|title=Six new select committees announced, Anwar heads reforms caucus|date=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|language=Malay|accessdate=27 May 2010}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref name=\"PRU13 election results\">{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"The Star GE14\">{{cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/|title=The Star Online GE14|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=24 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref>  \n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots<br />cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[1995 Malaysian general election|1995]]\n|rowspan=7|'''[[Jeli (federal constituency)|Jeli]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Mustapa<br />Mohamed'''}}<br />([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''13,301''