yce 2018, {{ISBN|978-3-947261-08-6}}.\n* Friedhelm Rathjen: ''Let It Be. Die Beatles im Apple-Studio, 21.\u201331. Januar 1969''. S\u00fcdwesth\u00f6rn: Edition ReJoyce 2019, {{ISBN|978-3-947261-09-3}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101129043017/http://www.norwegianwood.org/beatles/disko/uklp/letitbe.htm Recording data and notes]\n* [https://www.npr.org/programs/asc/archives/live031403/ ''The Lost Beatle Tapes'' / ''The Making of Let It Be'']\n* [http://www.britishbeatlesfanclub.co.uk/ The British Beatles Fanclub]\n\n{{Let It Be}}\n{{The Beatles albums}}\n{{Phil Spector}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2015}}\n\n[[Category:1970 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Phil Spector]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Apple Studios]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Abbey Road Studios]]\n[[Category:Apple Records albums]]\n[[Category:The Beatles albums]]\n[[Category:The Beatles soundtracks]]\n[[Category:1970 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Apple Records soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Film soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by George Martin]]\n", "name_user": "212.143.104.25", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharts)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Let_It_Be_(Beatles_album)"}
{"title_page": "Elaine Constantine", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2010}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Elaine Constantine \n| image         = \n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth year and age |1965}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bury, Lancashire]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| nationality   = [[British people|British]]\n| field         = [[Photography]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n}}\n'''Elaine Constantine''' (born 1965 in Bury, Lancashire) is a BAFTA nominated writer/director and photographer, globally recognised for her colourful and upbeat fashion imagery of confident young women.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Photography===\nConstantine came to prominence in the 1990s due to work published in ''The Face'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Lauren|last1=Cochrane|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Northern Soul: 'We gravitated towards each other when we clocked a like-minded girl at an all-nighter'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion-blog/2014/oct/17/northern-soul-film-fashion-freedom-equality|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 October 2014|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Her energetic and honest take on young women attracted international interest when she was regularly commissioned by Italian ''Vogue'' editor, Franca Sozzani and US ''Vogue'' editor Anna Wintour.\n\n====Exhibitions====\nConstantine's first solo show was at Marion de Beaupre's Gallerie 213, Paris, in 1998. In 2002 Constantine exhibited ''Tea Dance'', a show that documented the elderly tea dance culture of Northern England. ''Tea Dance'' has toured Paris, London, Rome, Amsterdam and Moscow.\n\n====Art collections====\nConstantine's work has been exhibited at London's [[The Photographers' Gallery]], [[Tate Britain]]'s ''Look at Me'' exhibition, curated by [[Val Williams]], and the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A's]] ''Imperfect Beauty'' exhibition, curated by [[Charlotte Cotton]]. A series of Constantine's prints are held in the photography collection at the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person-list.php?search=sas&firstRun=true&sText=Elaine+Constantine|title=National Portrait Gallery \"search the collections\", Elaine Constantine.|last=|first=|date=|website=NPG.org.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n\n====Editorial====\nConstantine has contributed to American, French and Italian ''Vogue.''<ref>{{cite news|first1=Alfred|last1=Hickling|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Elaine Constantine, Castlefield Gallery, Manchester|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2002/apr/29/art.artsfeatures1|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 April 2002|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Her commercial clients have included Adidas, Alberto Bianni, Anna Molinari, Burberry, Clarins, Diesel, Gucci, Hunter, Lacoste, Levi's, Nike, Shiseido and Vivienne Westwood.\n\n===Feature film===\nIn 2000 Constantine learned to screen write in order to create the feature-length screenplay for a film that would tell the story of her music and cultural obsession, [[Northern Soul]].<ref>{{cite news|first1=Bob|last1=Stanley|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Britain's got talcum: Northern Soul, the film|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/aug/31/northern-soul-elaine-constantine|newspaper=The Guardian|date=31 August 2011|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> After rejections from producers,<ref name=\"guardian-gant\">{{cite news|first1=Charles|last1=Gant|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Elaine Constantine: \u2018You may have a shit job, but you iron your clothes and polish your shoes\u2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/05/elaine-constantine-interview-northern-soul|newspaper=The Guardian|date=5 February 2015|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> she set up Stubborn Heart Productions and in late summer 2012 Constantine returned to the north of England to direct the debut feature film, ''Northern Soul.''\n\nThe film tells the Story of two Northern DJ's whose worlds are changed forever when they discover black American soul music. The film was released in October 2014 by Universal<ref name=\"guardian-gant\"/> and reached the box office top 10 on its opening weekend despite a relatively limited distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2014/oct/21/northern-soul-uk-box-office-teenage-mutant-ninja-turtles|title=Northern Soul is a surprise top 10 hit at the UK box office as the Turtles roll in|first=Charles|last=Gant|date=21 October 2014|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Nadia|last1=Khomami|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Niche northern soul film set to hit big time as social media fuels demand for screenings|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/12/northern-soul-movie-cinema-screenings-social-media-fuels-demand|newspaper=The Observer|date=11 October 2014|issn=0029-7712|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film received nominations from both, The British Independent Film Awards, and the British Academy Awards (BAFTA).<ref name=\"bafta\">{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2015/film|title=Film in 2015|publisher=|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> It also won the NME's award for Film of the Year, which was a public vote.<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/various-artists-1218-1207628|title=The full winners list at NME Awards 2015 with Austin, Texas revealed|first=NME News|last=Desk|date=18 February 2015|website=NME}}</ref>\n\nConstantine's book, of the same title, ''Northern Soul (An Illustrated History)'' was published by Random House' Virgin Books and co-edited by Gareth Sweeney, a factual and oral account of northern soul culture.\nThe soundtrack, released by Demon Music, also of the same title, entered the top ten when released and went to the top of the soul chart.\n\n==Awards==\n* 1998: [[John Kobal]] Foundation's Award\n* 2002: [[Creative Review]]'s Award for Best Up and Coming Promo Director\n* 2005: [[Royal Photographic Society]]'s Terence Donovan Achievement Award\n* 2015: London Critics Circle Breakthrough British Filmmaker Award&nbsp;\u2014 Nominated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criticscircle.org.uk/film/?ID=404|title=The London Critics' Circle Film Section|publisher=|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015: NME Best film of 2014 - Winner<ref name=\"nme\"/>\n* 2015: BAFTA Outstanding Debut for a Writer, Director or Producer Award \u2014 Nominated.<ref name=\"bafta\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.industryart.com/artists/elaineconstantine/ Industry Art] - Constantine's Representation\n* [http://www.northernsoulthefilm.com ''Northern Soul''] - Official website\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constantine, Elaine}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English women photographers]]\n[[Category:People from Bury, Greater Manchester]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2010}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Elaine Constantine \n| image         = \n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth year and age |1965}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bury, Lancashire]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| nationality   = [[British people|British]]\n| field         = [[Photography]]\n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n}}\n'''Elaine Constantine''' (born 1965 in Bury, Lancashire) is a BAFTA nominated writer/director and photographer, globally recognised for her colourful and upbeat fashion imagery of confident young women.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Photography===\nConstantine came to prominence in the 1990s due to work published in ''The Face'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Lauren|last1=Cochrane|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Northern Soul: 'We gravitated towards each other when we clocked a like-minded girl at an all-nighter'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion-blog/2014/oct/17/northern-soul-film-fashion-freedom-equality|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 October 2014|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Her energetic and honest take on young women attracted international interest when she was regularly commissioned by Italian ''Vogue'' editor, Franca Sozzani and US ''Vogue'' editor Anna Wintour.\n\n====Exhibitions====\nConstantine's first solo show was at Marion de Beaupre's Gallerie 213, Paris, in 1998. In 2002 Constantine exhibited ''Tea Dance'', a show that documented the elderly tea dance culture of Northern England. ''Tea Dance'' has toured Paris, London, Rome, Amsterdam and Moscow.\n\n====Art collections====\nConstantine's work has been exhibited at London's [[The Photographers' Gallery]], [[Tate Britain]]'s ''Look at Me'' exhibition, curated by [[Val Williams]], and the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A's]] ''Imperfect Beauty'' exhibition, curated by [[Charlotte Cotton]]. A series of Constantine's prints are held in the photography collection at the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]].\n\n====Editorial====\nConstantine has contributed to American, French and Italian ''Vogue.''<ref>{{cite news|first1=Alfred|last1=Hickling|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Elaine Constantine, Castlefield Gallery, Manchester|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2002/apr/29/art.artsfeatures1|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 April 2002|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Her commercial clients have included Adidas, Alberto Bianni, Anna Molinari, Burberry, Clarins, Diesel, Gucci, Hunter, Lacoste, Levi's, Nike, Shiseido and Vivienne Westwood.\n\n===Feature film===\nIn 2000 Constantine learned to screen write in order to create the feature-length screenplay for a film that would tell the story of her music and cultural obsession, [[Northern Soul]].<ref>{{cite news|first1=Bob|last1=Stanley|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Britain's got talcum: Northern Soul, the film|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/aug/31/northern-soul-elaine-constantine|newspaper=The Guardian|date=31 August 2011|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> After rejections from producers,<ref name=\"guardian-gant\">{{cite news|first1=Charles|last1=Gant|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Elaine Constantine: \u2018You may have a shit job, but you iron your clothes and polish your shoes\u2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/05/elaine-constantine-interview-northern-soul|newspaper=The Guardian|date=5 February 2015|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> she set up Stubborn Heart Productions and in late summer 2012 Constantine returned to the north of England to direct the debut feature film, ''Northern Soul.''\n\nThe film tells the Story of two Northern DJ's whose worlds are changed forever when they discover black American soul music. The film was released in October 2014 by Universal<ref name=\"guardian-gant\"/> and reached the box office top 10 on its opening weekend despite a relatively limited distribution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2014/oct/21/northern-soul-uk-box-office-teenage-mutant-ninja-turtles|title=Northern Soul is a surprise top 10 hit at the UK box office as the Turtles roll in|first=Charles|last=Gant|date=21 October 2014|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Nadia|last1=Khomami|accessdate=2019-07-03|title=Niche northern soul film set to hit big time as social media fuels demand for screenings|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/12/northern-soul-movie-cinema-screenings-social-media-fuels-demand|newspaper=The Observer|date=11 October 2014|issn=0029-7712|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film received nominations from both, The British Independent Film Awards, and the British Academy Awards (BAFTA).<ref name=\"bafta\">{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2015/film|title=Film in 2015|publisher=|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> It also won the NME's award for Film of the Year, which was a public vote.<ref name=\"nme\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/various-artists-1218-1207628|title=The full winners list at NME Awards 2015 with Austin, Texas revealed|first=NME News|last=Desk|date=18 February 2015|website=NME}}</ref>\n\nConstantine's book, of the same title, ''Northern Soul (An Illustrated History)'' was published by Random House' Virgin Books and co-edited by Gareth Sweeney, a factual and oral account of northern soul culture.\nThe soundtrack, released by Demon Music, also of the same title, entered the top ten when released and went to the top of the soul chart.\n\n==Awards==\n* 1998: [[John Kobal]] Foundation's Award\n* 2002: [[Creative Review]]'s Award for Best Up and Coming Promo Director\n* 2005: [[Royal Photographic Society]]'s Terence Donovan Achievement Award\n* 2015: London Critics Circle Breakthrough British Filmmaker Award&nbsp;\u2014 Nominated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criticscircle.org.uk/film/?ID=404|title=The London Critics' Circle Film Section|publisher=|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015: NME Best film of 2014 - Winner<ref name=\"nme\"/>\n* 2015: BAFTA Outstanding Debut for a Writer, Director or Producer Award \u2014 Nominated.<ref name=\"bafta\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.industryart.com/artists/elaineconstantine/ Industry Art] - Constantine's Representation\n* [http://www.northernsoulthefilm.com ''Northern Soul''] - Official website\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constantine, Elaine}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English women photographers]]\n[[Category:People from Bury, Greater 