{"title_page": "Guvna B", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2012}}\n{{tone|date=December 2013}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Guvna B\n| image           =\n| caption         = Guvna B performing at BCDO Festival 2013\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Isaac Charles Borquaye\n| alias           = Guvna B\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1989|06|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Custom House, Newham]], England\n| death_date      =\n| genre           = [[Gospel music#British Black Gospel|Gospel]], [[contemporary Christian music|CCM]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Grime (music)|grime]], [[drum and bass]]\n| years_active    = 2007&ndash;present\n| label           =\n| occupation      = Christian rapper, songwriter and author\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.guvnab.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Isaac Borquaye''' (born 13 June 1989), better known as '''Guvna B''', is a double [[MOBO Awards|MOBO Award]] winning rapper and author from [[Custom House, Newham|Custom House]], [[London]]. His album, ''Hands are Made For Working'' (2018), has been streamed over 5 million times and debuted at number 2 on the UK Hip Hop/Rap Albums Charts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Chad |title=Guvna B Reaches number 2 |url=https://rapzilla.com/2018-05-guvna-b-reaches-2-itunes-uk-rap-charts/ |website=Rapzilla |publisher=Rapzilla |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> It was also the UK's highest charting non-explicit rap album that year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borquaye |first1=Isaac |title=Allo Mate About |url=https://allomate.co.uk/get-involved/ |website=Guvna B |publisher=Isaac Borquaye |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> His debut book ''Unpopular Culture'' (2017) became an [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] bestseller. His breakthrough album ''Secret World'' (2015) was the first rap album to top the [[Official Christian & Gospel Albums Chart|Official Christian & Gospel Albums Charts]]. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Charts |first1=Official |title=Guvna B becomes first rapper to top charts |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/guvna-b-becomes-first-rapper-to-top-the-official-christian-and-gospel__3084/ |website=Official Charts |publisher=Official Charts |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> The album featured hit single \"Nothing But The Blood\" which has received over 2 million views on [[YouTube]]. <ref>{{cite web |last1=B |first1=Guvna |title=Nothing But The Blood |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C-be3I6RulQ |website=Youtube |publisher=Allo Mate Records |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nGuvna B is widely considered an influential and important voice within [[Grime (music genre)|grime]] and [[British hip hop|British hip-hop]] because of his inspiring and uplifting lyricism and his views on [[youth culture]]. He has appeared numerous times on [[Sky News]], [[BBC]], and [[Channel 4]] to discuss topics which affect young people from underprivileged communities, and how they can reach their full potential. \n\n==Biography==\n\nGuvna B was born in London, England in June 1989, to Ghanaian parents from [[Accra]].<ref name=\"positivelygospel1\">{{cite web |author=Sarah Hearn |url=http://www.positivelygospel.com/2013/06/18/guvna-b-uk-singer-makes-big-splash-across-the-pond/ |title=Guvna B: UK Singer Makes Big Splash Across The Pond |publisher=PositivelyGospel.com |date=18 June 2013 |accessdate=1 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102194119/http://www.positivelygospel.com/2013/06/18/guvna-b-uk-singer-makes-big-splash-across-the-pond/ |archive-date=2 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Looking back on growing up in Custom House (in East London),<ref name=top-spot/> he stated: \"My upbringing helped me find my faith in Jesus. The negative things I saw in my society inspired me to do better and inspire people to be the best they can be instead of becoming stereotypical products of a negative environment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislime.net/interviews/community/Guvna_B |title=Guvna B > Community & Support Interview |publisher=Thisislime.net |date= |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref> He later graduated from [[University of Hertfordshire]].<ref name=\"positivelygospel1\"/> His music addresses life issues such as peer pressure.<ref name=top-spot>{{cite web|last=Dixon |first=Marcia |url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/guvna-b-hits-top-spot |title=Guvna B hits the top spot |publisher=The Voice Online |date=16 June 2013 |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Guvna B won the [[MOBO Awards|MOBO Award]] for Best Gospel Act.<ref name=\"MOBO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/mobo-awards-2010-winners|title=MOBO Awards 2010 Winners!|work=MOBO.com|accessdate=30 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724151015/http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/mobo-awards-2010-winners|archive-date=24 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"MOBOBBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/1xtra/mobos/2010/winners/|title=MOBO Awards 2010 winners|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref> \n\nHis story was shared with many when he was featured in the 22 March 2013 issue of the music industry magazine ''[[Music Week]]'' in a feature covering the gospel music industry in the UK.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=GuvnaB|author=Guvna B|number=316970937285226496|date=27 March 2013|title=Shouts to music week! They published this article on Christian and Gospel music.}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2013, Guvna B launched his own urban clothing brand, Allo Mate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ireadmex.com/2013/01/allo-mate-the-clothing-line-from-guvna-b/ |title=\u2018Allo Mate\u2019 The Clothing Line From Guvna B \u2039 M.E.X Magazine |publisher=Ireadmex.com |date= |accessdate=1 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102193726/http://ireadmex.com/2013/01/allo-mate-the-clothing-line-from-guvna-b/ |archive-date=2 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2017, [[Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge|SPCK Publishing]] published his debut book, ''Unpopular Culture''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radarradio.com/blog/unpopular-culture-an-interview-with-guvna-b|title=Unpopular Culture: An Interview With Guvna B - Radar Radio|publisher=|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''The Narrow Road'' (31 May 2008)\n* ''Scrapbook ''(1 January 2011) \n* ''Next Ting 140'' (18 August 2011)\n* ''Odd1Out'' (26 May 2013)\n* ''Scrapbook II'' (31 March 2014)\n* ''Something for the Summer'' (3 August 2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/something-for-the-summer/id895862145|title=Something For the Summer by Guvna B on Apple Music|website=iTunes|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Secret World'' (20 November 2015) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/secret-world/id1054342527|title=Secret World by Guvna B on Apple Music|website=iTunes|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Hands are Made for Working'' (18 May 2018)\n* ''everywhere + nowhere'' (3 April 2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Year\n!Category\n!Award\n!Result\n|-\n||2009\n|[[Gospel Music Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2009\n|{{won}}\n|-\n||2009\n|[[Urban Music Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Act 2009\n|{{won}}<ref>[http://www.urbanmusicawards.net/uk_news.php?id=118&start=0&limit=10 The Urban Music Award's UK return for another successful night] ''(sic.)'', 3 November 2009, UMA website</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=May |first=Jenny |url=http://bandweblogs.com/blog/2009/11/02/the-7th-annual-urban-music-awards-2009-bloomsbury-theatre-london-review/ |title=Guvna B wins UMA for Best Gospel 2009 |publisher=Bandweblogs.com |date=2 November 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Act 2010\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"MOBO\" /><ref name=\"MOBOBBC\" />\n|-\n||2011\n|[[Official Mixtape Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2009\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n||2012\n|RARE Rising Stars\n|UK's Top 10 Black Students 2012\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rarerecruitment.co.uk/rrs2012/07-Isaac-_Guvna-B_Borquaye.php#.UsLkCXkzLnc|title=Guvna B wins RARE Rising Star Award - 2012|publisher=2011 Rare Recruitment Ltd. |accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n||2013\n|[[Urban Music Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2013\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigslutz.co.uk/fuse-odg-emerges-as-king-from-the-urban-music-awards-2013/|title=Fuse ODG Emerges as King From The Urban Music Awards 2013|publisher=Boostdevelopers|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n||2013\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2013\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n||2013\n|[[Ghana UK-Based Achievement Awards]]\n|Music Artist of the Year  2013\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n||2016\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2016\n|{{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.guvnab.com/}}\n* {{YouTube|u=GuvnaMusic}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guvna B}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:Grime music artists]]\n[[Category:People from Canning Town]]\n[[Category:Black British male rappers]]\n[[Category:Black British musicians]]\n[[Category:British performers of Christian hip hop music]]\n[[Category:Urban contemporary gospel musicians]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2012}}\n{{tone|date=December 2013}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Guvna B\n| image           =\n| caption         = Guvna B performing at BCDO Festival 2013\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Isaac Charles Borquaye\n| alias           = Guvna B\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1989|06|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Custom House, Newham]], England\n| death_date      =\n| genre           = [[Gospel music#British Black Gospel|Gospel]], [[contemporary Christian music|CCM]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Grime (music)|grime]], [[drum and bass]]\n| years_active    = 2007&ndash;present\n| label           =\n| occupation      = Christian rapper, songwriter and author\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.guvnab.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Isaac Borquaye''' (born 13 June 1989), better known as '''Guvna B''', is a double [[MOBO Awards|MOBO Award]] winning rapper and author from [[Custom House, Newham|Custom House]], [[London]]. His latest album, ''Hands are Made For Working'' (2018), has been streamed over 5 million times and debuted at number 2 on the UK Hip Hop/Rap Albums Charts.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Chad |title=Guvna B Reaches number 2 |url=https://rapzilla.com/2018-05-guvna-b-reaches-2-itunes-uk-rap-charts/ |website=Rapzilla |publisher=Rapzilla |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> It was also the UK's highest charting non-explicit rap album that year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borquaye |first1=Isaac |title=Allo Mate About |url=https://allomate.co.uk/get-involved/ |website=Guvna B |publisher=Isaac Borquaye |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> His debut book ''Unpopular Culture'' (2017) became an [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] bestseller. His breakthrough album ''Secret World'' (2015) was the first rap album to top the [[Official Christian & Gospel Albums Chart|Official Christian & Gospel Albums Charts]]. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Charts |first1=Official |title=Guvna B becomes first rapper to top charts |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/guvna-b-becomes-first-rapper-to-top-the-official-christian-and-gospel__3084/ |website=Official Charts |publisher=Official Charts |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> The album featured hit single \"Nothing But The Blood\" which has received over 2 million views on [[YouTube]]. <ref>{{cite web |last1=B |first1=Guvna |title=Nothing But The Blood |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C-be3I6RulQ |website=Youtube |publisher=Allo Mate Records |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nGuvna B is widely considered an influential and important voice within [[Grime (music genre)|grime]] and [[British hip hop|British hip-hop]] because of his inspiring and uplifting lyricism and his views on [[youth culture]]. He has appeared numerous times on [[Sky News]], [[BBC]], and [[Channel 4]] to discuss topics which affect young people from underprivileged communities, and how they can reach their full potential. \n\n==Biography==\n\nGuvna B was born in London, England in June 1989, to Ghanaian parents from [[Accra]].<ref name=\"positivelygospel1\">{{cite web |author=Sarah Hearn |url=http://www.positivelygospel.com/2013/06/18/guvna-b-uk-singer-makes-big-splash-across-the-pond/ |title=Guvna B: UK Singer Makes Big Splash Across The Pond |publisher=PositivelyGospel.com |date=18 June 2013 |accessdate=1 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102194119/http://www.positivelygospel.com/2013/06/18/guvna-b-uk-singer-makes-big-splash-across-the-pond/ |archive-date=2 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Looking back on growing up in Custom House (in East London),<ref name=top-spot/> he stated: \"My upbringing helped me find my faith in Jesus. The negative things I saw in my society inspired me to do better and inspire people to be the best they can be instead of becoming stereotypical products of a negative environment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislime.net/interviews/community/Guvna_B |title=Guvna B > Community & Support Interview |publisher=Thisislime.net |date= |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref> He later graduated from [[University of Hertfordshire]].<ref name=\"positivelygospel1\"/> His music addresses life issues such as peer pressure.<ref name=top-spot>{{cite web|last=Dixon |first=Marcia |url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/guvna-b-hits-top-spot |title=Guvna B hits the top spot |publisher=The Voice Online |date=16 June 2013 |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Guvna B won the [[MOBO Awards|MOBO Award]] for Best Gospel Act.<ref name=\"MOBO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/mobo-awards-2010-winners|title=MOBO Awards 2010 Winners!|work=MOBO.com|accessdate=30 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724151015/http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/mobo-awards-2010-winners|archive-date=24 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"MOBOBBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/1xtra/mobos/2010/winners/|title=MOBO Awards 2010 winners|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref> \n\nHis story was shared with many when he was featured in the 22 March 2013 issue of the music industry magazine ''[[Music Week]]'' in a feature covering the gospel music industry in the UK.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=GuvnaB|author=Guvna B|number=316970937285226496|date=27 March 2013|title=Shouts to music week! They published this article on Christian and Gospel music.}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2013, Guvna B launched his own urban clothing brand, Allo Mate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ireadmex.com/2013/01/allo-mate-the-clothing-line-from-guvna-b/ |title=\u2018Allo Mate\u2019 The Clothing Line From Guvna B \u2039 M.E.X Magazine |publisher=Ireadmex.com |date= |accessdate=1 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102193726/http://ireadmex.com/2013/01/allo-mate-the-clothing-line-from-guvna-b/ |archive-date=2 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2017, [[Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge|SPCK Publishing]] published his debut book, ''Unpopular Culture''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radarradio.com/blog/unpopular-culture-an-interview-with-guvna-b|title=Unpopular Culture: An Interview With Guvna B - Radar Radio|publisher=|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''The Narrow Road'' (31 May 2008)\n* ''Scrapbook ''(1 January 2011) \n* ''Next Ting 140'' (18 August 2011)\n* ''Odd1Out'' (26 May 2013)\n* ''Scrapbook II'' (31 March 2014)\n* ''Something for the Summer'' (3 August 2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/something-for-the-summer/id895862145|title=Something For the Summer by Guvna B on Apple Music|website=iTunes|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Secret World'' (20 November 2015) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/secret-world/id1054342527|title=Secret World by Guvna B on Apple Music|website=iTunes|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Hands are Made for Working'' (18 May 2018)\n* ''everywhere + nowhere'' (3 April 2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Year\n!Category\n!Award\n!Result\n|-\n||2009\n|[[Gospel Music Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2009\n|{{won}}\n|-\n||2009\n|[[Urban Music Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Act 2009\n|{{won}}<ref>[http://www.urbanmusicawards.net/uk_news.php?id=118&start=0&limit=10 The Urban Music Award's UK return for another successful night] ''(sic.)'', 3 November 2009, UMA website</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=May |first=Jenny |url=http://bandweblogs.com/blog/2009/11/02/the-7th-annual-urban-music-awards-2009-bloomsbury-theatre-london-review/ |title=Guvna B wins UMA for Best Gospel 2009 |publisher=Bandweblogs.com |date=2 November 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Act 2010\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"MOBO\" /><ref name=\"MOBOBBC\" />\n|-\n||2011\n|[[Official Mixtape Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2009\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n||2012\n|RARE Rising Stars\n|UK's Top 10 Black Students 2012\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rarerecruitment.co.uk/rrs2012/07-Isaac-_Guvna-B_Borquaye.php#.UsLkCXkzLnc|title=Guvna B wins RARE Rising Star Award - 2012|publisher=2011 Rare Recruitment Ltd. |accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n||2013\n|[[Urban Music Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2013\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigslutz.co.uk/fuse-odg-emerges-as-king-from-the-urban-music-awards-2013/|title=Fuse ODG Emerges as King From The Urban Music Awards 2013|publisher=Boostdevelopers|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n||2013\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2013\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n||2013\n|[[Ghana UK-Based Achievement Awards]]\n|Music Artist of the Year  2013\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n||2016\n|[[MOBO Awards]]\n|Best Gospel Artist 2016\n|{{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.guvnab.com/}}\n* {{YouTube|u=GuvnaMusic}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guvna B}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male rappers]]\n[[Category:Grime music artists]]\n[[Category:People from Canning Town]]\n[[Category:Black British male rappers]]\n[[Category:Black British musicians]]\n[[Category:British performers of Christian hip hop music]]\n[[Category:Urban contemporary gospel musicians]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Rappers from London]]\n", "name_user": "Thomas Hasson", "label": "safe", "comment": "He has released a new album this week, making Hands are made for working no longer his latest album", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guvna_B"}
{"title_page": "Origins of the French Foreign Legion", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Foreign Legion Chinese hat Bastille Day 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Mark of Originality of the actual French Foreign Legion, the utilization of the \"[[Turkish crescent|Chinese Hat]]\" ({{lang-fr|Chapeau Chinois}}) marks the history of this corps along with the [[French Foreign Legion Music Band (MLE)|Music]].]]\n\nThe [[French Foreign Legion]] was established in 1831 with the aim of recruiting foreign nationals into the [[France|French]] military service. The Foreign Legion was deeply rooted in the [[French conquest of Algeria]] and France's colonial expansion. The Legion is distinctive in that all its recruits are volunteers, while other national foreign regiments are conscripts or prisoners of war (although this was not the case for the 1831 Legion).\n\n== Foreign nationals in service of France==\n=== Ancien R\u00e9gime ===\nThe [[List of French monarchs|French monarchy]] had hired foreign soldiers since before the [[Bourbon Restoration]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Crowdy|first=Terry|title=French Revolutionary Infantry 1789-1802|publisher=|year=|isbn=1-84176-660-7|location=|pages=13 and 16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1346, [[Philip VI of France]] deployed 15,000 Genovese at the [[Battle of Crecy]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The 13th century and 14th century also saw the appearance of [[free company|grand companies of Scots]], Castillans, Savoyards, Swiss, and Dutch soldiers of given chiefs or princes.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nDuring the reign of [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]], the French Army consisted of 20%-30% non-French soldiers. Additionally, Louis XI employed a [[Garde Ecossaise]], and 6000 Swiss in 1480.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=11}}\n\n[[Francis I of France|Francis I]] formed a mostly foreign infantry corps and created the {{ill|Foreign Regiments of the Ancien R\u00e9gime|fr|R\u00e9giments \u00e9trangers au service de l'Ancien R\u00e9gime}}.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n \n[[Image:Jean Duplessi-Bertaux 001.jpg|thumb|right|[[10 August (French Revolution)|Day of August 10, 1792]] ''La Prise des Tuileries'' (The taking of the Tuileries). The red uniforms of the [[Swiss]] are distinct from the other combatants.]]\nDuring the [[Seven Years' War]], France mustered 32 foreign regiments: twelve German units, ten Swiss, seven Irish, two Italian and one Scottish.{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=10}}\n\nFollowing the abolition of the monarchy during the [[French Revolution]], the [[National Legislative Assembly (France)|National Legislative Assembly]] allowed the use of foreign soldiers and created foreign volunteer units, such as the {{ill|Foreign Volunteer Units in Service of France|fr|Unit\u00e9s de volontaires \u00e9trangers au service de la France}}. Afterward, the National Legislative Assembly, in the decree of July 26, 1792, stated that \"If the Allied Kings deploy numerous Armies against the free peoples, it is important for them to admit into their ranks all the men whom a sublime impulse calls to fight for the sacred cause of Liberty.\" Accordingly, the ''L\u00e9gion Franche Etrang\u00e8re'' was created on August 1. A [[Germanic Legion]], an {{ill|Italian Legion|fr|L\u00e9gion Italique}}, a [[Batavian Legion]], and a [[Polish Legions (Napoleonic period)|Polish Legion]] were formed.{{sfn|Poirmeur|1931|p=12}} During this period of 146,000 available soldiers, 42,000 were not French.{{sfn|Blond|1981|p=25}}\n\n=== Empire ===\nThe conquests of the [[First French Empire]] led to great demand for foreign troops, with the proportion of non-French national soldiers reaching record proportions. In Spain, one-sixth of formations were foreign soldiers.{{sfn|Blond|1981|p=25}}\n \nAfter his rise to power, [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]] recruited 4,000 Swiss{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}} and then more than 90,000 in the course of his reign.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} They formed the {{ill|Valaison Battalion|fr|bataillon Valaisan}}, in 1805.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn 1805, Russian and Austrian prisoners composed the {{ill|Regiment of Tour d'Auvergne|fr|R\u00e9giment de La Tour d'Auvergne}} and the {{ill|Regiment of Isembourg|fr|R\u00e9giment d'Isembourg}}.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The two were later renamed the 1st Foreign Regiment and 2nd Foreign Regiment{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} and later dissolved in 1814.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe {{ill|Piedmontese Legion|fr|L\u00e9gion Pi\u00e9montaise}} or ''L\u00e9gion du Midi'', created in 1803, was composed of former French soldiers and recruits from the [[Departments of France#Departments of the Napoleonic Empire in Europe|French departments of Italy]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Napoleon's forces would also include the Spanish Pioneers, the {{ill|Catalonian Regiment|fr|R\u00e9giment de Catalogne}}, the {{ill|Hanoverian Legion|fr|L\u00e9gion hanovrienne}}, the Egyptian [[Mamluks]], and the [[Portuguese Legion (Napoleonic Wars)|Portuguese Legion]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nBetween 1806 and 1814, 60 foreign units were constituted and commanded by 136 generals.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}} A large part of these Europeans were volunteers.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Conscripts came only from the regions annexed by the Empire.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n \nIt is estimated that of the 400,000 men who crossed the [[Neman]] River towards [[Moscow]] or [[Smolensk]], just 120,000 were actually French.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}} During the [[Hundred Days]], Napoleon assembled eight foreign regiments.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n=== Restoration ===\nUnder [[Louis XVIII of France]], 14,000 Swiss soldiers in six regiments and four regiments, composed of [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] and Spanish, constituted the Royal Foreign Legion in 1815.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}}\n\n== Creation of the French Foreign Legion ==\n=== Causes ===\nThe creation of the Foreign Legion was in large part was due to the aftermath following the [[July Revolution]].{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984|p=9}}\n\nFollowing the purge of the army after the [[July Revolution]],{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984|p=9}} Louis Philippe I was in need of a way to occupy those seen as dangerous or restless elements of the regular army, whether French or foreign. The Legion became a depository for those who did not conform to the governing agenda. There was also concern over those seen as foreign insurrectionists and volunteer fighters which had journeyed in the hopes of continuing the [[French Revolution|1789 Revolution]].{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=37}} To the State, they threatened the stability of the kingdom and its economy it became urgent to group and distance them.{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=34}}\n\nIn addition, despite the [[enthusiasm]] showcased by the men in the [[Invasion of Algiers in 1830]], morale was at a low{{sfn|Blond|1981|p=25}} and the war, deemed very unpopular. Louis Philipe I was a pacifist and did not want to weigh the national and military opinion on a costly conquest which would endanger French lives and thus sought to use foreign troops. However, since the Kingdom was reduced, it was not feasible to recruit contingents in occupied lands such as during Napoleon's era. Accordingly, a new sort of troop was required.\n\n=== Creation by Royal Ordinance ===\nThe French Foreign Legion was created by Royal Ordinance on March 9, 1831. The ordinance had nine articles.\n{{verse translation|lang=fr|Louis-Philippe, roi des Fran\u00e7ais, \u00e0 tous pr\u00e9sents et \u00e0 venir salut ;\n\nVu la loi du 9 mars 1831 :\n\nSur le rapport de notre Ministre Secr\u00e9taire d\u2019\u00c9tat au D\u00e9partement de la Guerre : Nous avons ordonn\u00e9 et ordonnons ce qui suit :\n\nArt. 1 - Il sera form\u00e9 une L\u00e9gion compos\u00e9e d\u2019\u00c9trangers. Cette L\u00e9gion prendra la d\u00e9nomination de L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re.\nArt. 2 - Les bataillons de la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re auront la m\u00eame formation que les Bataillons d'infanterie de ligne.\nArt. 3 - Pour la solde, les masses et son administration, la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re sera assimil\u00e9e aux r\u00e9giments fran\u00e7ais. L'uniforme sera bleu avec le simple passepoil garance et le pantalon de m\u00eame couleur, les boutons seront jaunes et porteront les mots L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re.\nArt. 4 - Tout \u00c9tranger qui voudra faire partie de la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re ne pourra y \u00eatre admis qu'apr\u00e8s avoir contract\u00e9, devant un sous-intendant militaire, un engagement volontaire.\nArt. 5 - La dur\u00e9e de l'engagement sera de trois ans au moins et de cinq ans au plus.\nArt. 6 - Pour \u00eatre re\u00e7us \u00e0 s'engager, les \u00c9tranger devront n'avoir pas plus de quarante ans, et avoir au moins dix-huit ans accomplis, et la taille de 1m55. Ils devront en outre \u00eatre porteur d'un certificat d'acceptation de l'autorit\u00e9 militaire constatant qu'ils ont les qualit\u00e9s requises pour faire un bon service.\nArt. 7 - En l'absence de pi\u00e8ces, l\u2019\u00c9tranger sera envoy\u00e9 devant l'Officier G\u00e9n\u00e9ral qui d\u00e9cidera si l'engagement peut \u00eatre re\u00e7u.\nArt. 8 - Les militaires faisant partie de la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re se pourront rengager pour deux ans au moins et cinq ans au plus. Les rengagements ne donneront droit \u00e0 une haute paie qu'autant que les militaires auront accompli cinq ans de service.\nArt. 9 - Notre Ministre Secr\u00e9taire d\u2019\u00c9tat au D\u00e9partement de la Guerre est charg\u00e9 de l'ex\u00e9cution de la pr\u00e9sente ordonnance. Par le Roi :\n\nLe Ministre Secr\u00e9taire d\u2019\u00c9tat de la Guerre Sign\u00e9 : Mar\u00e9chal SOULT Duc de Dalmatie\nsign\u00e9 : LOUIS-PHILIPPE\n|Louis-Philippe, King of the French, to all present and to those to come greetings;\n\nLaw decree of March 9, 1831:\n\nOn the report of our State Minister Secretary at the Ministry of War: We have ordained and we order as follows:\n\nArt. 1 - A Legion will be formed and composed of foreigners. This Legion will be known as the French Foreign Legion.\nArt. 2 - The battalions of the French Foreign Legion will have the same formation as the line infantry battalions.\nArt. 3 - For pay, masses and administration, the French Foreign Legion will be assimilated to French regiments. The uniform will be blue with simple ''passepoil garance'' and pants of the same color, the buttons will be yellow and inscribed with the words ''L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re''.\nArt. 4 - Every foreigner who wishes to be part of the French Foreign Legion, will only be admitted after having contracted, in front of a deputy superintendent, a volunteer enlistment.\nArt. 5 - The duration of the contract of enlistment will be at least three years or a maximum of five years.\nArt. 6 - To enlist, foreigners should not be more than forty and should be at least eighteen years old, with a minimum height of 1m55. They should be attested by and in possession of an acceptance certificate from the competent military authority, who asserts that they have the appropriate qualities for good and proper service.\nArt. 7 - In absence of credentials, the foreigner will be sent to the general officer, who will decide whether his engagement would be acceptable.\nArt. 8 - Military personnel of the French Foreign Legion can reenlist for a period of two and a maximum of five years. High pay is rightly warranted upon accomplishing five years of service.\nArt. 9 - Our State Secretary Minister to the Ministry of War is charged with executing this present ordinance.\n\nThe State Secretary War Minister Signed: Marshal SOULT, Duke of Dalmatia\nsigned: LOUIS-PHILIPE\n}}\n\n=== A challenging start ===\n[[File:Une compagnie de la 2e legion sur les champs de mars.jpg|thumb|A company of the [[2nd Foreign Legion (2LE)|Legion]] on the [[Champ de Mars]] in Paris (1836).]]\n\nThe Legion was formed around former Swiss regiments and the [[Hohenlohe Regiment|Hohenloe regiment]], who formed a nucleus of professional soldiers, however, the experience of recruits varied greatly. To the State, the Legion succeeded in diminishing the number of foreign exiled politicians and potential revolutionaries. It attracted both French and foreign nationals from all walks of life.{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=38}} Certain persons enlisted from a nonetheless motivated allure and voluntary spirit, the times helping and Africa still unknown, so adventurers also enlisted.{{sfn|Blond|1981}} Also, many friends of France, who were numerous, hoped to battle for the nation. Nevertheless, this created a motley corps, where soldiers rubbed elbows with anarchists. Inactivity in wait for assignments and [[nationalism]] of some, entailed high energies between communities, which entailed the need to have a more concise common frame.\n\nOfficers and [[non-commissioned officer]]s were needed;{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=39}} but those of the Imperial Army were too old already and unequal to the times. Foreign officers who had left their armies were not familiar with the [[French language]], and hailed from different armies or other branches of the military. Punishments were numerous and harsh with insubordination and desertion being common. In mid-May, the National Guard was called upon to prevent a possible rebellion. On that day, 20 soldiers were arrested.{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=44}}\n\nDespite these complications, less than six months after the royal ordinance,{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984|p=10}} five battalions were created, each with eight combat companies.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" align='center'\n|+ Nationalities by battalion \n! !! nationalities\n|-\n| 1st || Swiss and former of Hohenlohe\n|-\n| 2nd || Swiss and Germans \n|-\n| 3rd || Swiss and Germans \n|-\n| 4th || Spanish\n|-\n| 5th || Sardinians and Italians\n|-\n| 6th || Belgians and Dutch \n|}\n\n=== The beginnings ===\nStarting the month of August, the 1st, 2nd, 3rd and 5th battalions deployed to Algeria, counting a total of 78 Officers and 2,669 [[Non-commissioned officer|Sous-officiers]] and Legionnaires.{{sfn|Montagnon1999|p=15}}\n\nThe Legion was first preoccupied with [[Fortification|earthworks]] and accordingly gained their reputation as a {{ill|builder soldiers|fr|soldat b\u00e2tisseur}}, the essence base of the Legion. Accordingly, the Legion would build the route of Casbah in the region of Algiers, that of the {{ill|Emperor's Fort|fr|Fort de l'Empereur}}, or that of the belt of Algiers. The Legion also participated in the construction of many [[Forts]], including the Water Fort. During the construction of the works fevers, [[dysentery]] and [[cholera]] would kill or reform 3,200 men between 1831 and 1835.{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=50}}\n\n=== Baptism by fire ===\nApril 27, 1832, 300 men of the 3rd battalion began to secure the surrounding of Algiers and engaged in combat at Maison Carr\u00e9. On May 23, a detachment was exterminated: resulting in 26 fatalities.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=16}} The conquest of Algeria cost the French Foreign Legion: 27 Officers, 61 Sous-officiers and 756 Legionnaires.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=19}} Colonel Combes, arrived from [[Marseille]] with the first flag of the Legion offered by [[Ferdinand Philippe, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]], in the name of the [[List of French monarchs|King]].\n\nInscribed on the flag was: ''Le Roi des Fran\u00e7ais \u00e0 la L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re'' (\"King of the French in the French Foreign Legion\"). The troop was then known and distinguished.{{sfn|Messager|2007|pp=222\u2013223}}\n\nThe Legion fought at Sidi Chabal in November 1832, where the Spanish battalion distinguished itself. In March 1833, Legionnaires fought at Ouled Yacoub and Oule Attia, against [[Emir]] [[Emir Abdelkader|Abdelkader]] and the tribes of the [[Sig, Algeria|Sig]].\n\nThe Legion won a victory at [[Arzew]] on June 5 and took [[Mostaganem]] on July 27, 1833.\n\n1835 was marked by fighting at [[Battle of Macta|Moulay Ismael]] and cost the lives of a hundred Legionnaires.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=18}}\n\n== Spain and the end of the old Legion ==\n=== Goodwill to Spain ===\n{{See also|Carlism|First Carlist War}}\nOn June 28, 1843, the ambassadors of London, Lisbon, and Paris signed a treaty with Spain supporting Marie-Christina. France did not favor this treaty, because it did not want to interfere in Spanish affairs or risk compromising European peace,{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=21}} and so did not want to send the regular French Army. Sending the Foreign Legion allowed France to justify involvement.\n\nOn January 28, 1835, under pressure from [[Adolphe Thiers]], Minister of Interior, the Legion was ceded to the Queen of Spain. On June 29, a royal ordinance stipulated that the French Foreign Legion was no longer part of the French Army.{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=20}} The [[Army Corps]] had been ceded to Spain, and all Legionnaires embarked: the sick, imprisoned, and those on leave included. The men could not back out or they would face severe sanctions for insubordination.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=21}}\n\nOn July 30, 123 officers and 4,021 [[Non-commissioned officers|Sous-Officiers]] and Legionnaires embarked on [[French Navy|La Royal]]<ref>This was the traditional surname of the [[French Navy|French War Navy]].</ref> heading to Algeria.\n\nDuring a stopover at the [[Balearic Islands]], the battalions were reorganized, and all nationalities mixed together.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=22}}\n\n=== The fighting ===\nThe Legion in Spain became the French Auxiliary Division and their chief, colonel Bernelle, became [[Mar\u00e9chal de camp]] of the Spanish Armies. On arrival, the Legion entered the war against 5,000 Carlists in Catalonia. After several skirmishes in Navarre and Aragon, the Legion entered [[Pamplona]] on February 5, 1836 to encircle and isolate the province.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}}\n\nThe Legion often fought alone becoming more autonomous;{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984}} Bernelle supplemented his troops with three squadrons of lancers, a [[Howitzer]] battery for support, and a [[Company (military unit)|medical]] company. This was the beginning of the modern French Foreign Legion.\n\nDay after day, the Legion lost men. On April 15, 1836, losses had risen to 117 killed, 380 dead of wounds or disease, and 83 deserters.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999}} At Tirapequi on April 26, 500 Legionnaires repelled 3,500 Carlists at the cost of 90 dead{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}} and, on August 1, at [[Zubiri, Navarre|Zubiri]], the Legion all alone killed 1,200 Carlists in one battle.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}}\n\n=== The Legion abandoned ===\nIn Spain, the Legion became more and more isolated with reinforcements arriving sporadically.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}} Paris turned a deaf ear, equipment and supplies were insufficient, the pay was irregular, and decorations and advancement did not follow. [[Adolphe Thiers]], president of the council, refused them aid, saying that the Legion had been handed in full and entirely to Spain. Reaching a limit, Bernelle resigned and returned to France. The King didn't want to send reinforcements from the [[French Army|regular army]], out of fear of tiring the troops and becoming entrenched. In addition, the conquest of Algeria required reinforcements. The King did not want to divide his troops. The Legion was accordingly left to its fate.\n\n=== Misery and wandering ===\nThe Legion continued to fight, the lack of decent equipment aggravated by the particularly bitter winter of 1836\u20131837 in the plains of [[Aragon]]. With their pay in default and their living conditions poor, some joined the Carlists who were living off the land.\n\nAt the beginning of 1837, the Legion had only three battalions, then two; the Legion had been reduced in half since its arrival. However, the Legion continued to fight with a suicidal determination.{{sfn|Poirmeur|1931|p=26}}\n\nIn 1838, the Legion was a shadow of itself in poor living conditions, without resources, and surrounded by Carlists. It was not until December 8 that the Queen finally granted its dissolution. They left Zaragoza on January 2, 1839 and crossed the Pyrenees, starved and miserable. \n \nSome 6,000 had disembarked at Tarragona in 1835, but only 63 Officers and 50 troops returned.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=26}} During the Spanish odyssey, the King had created [[2nd Foreign Legion (2LE)|another Legion]].\n\n== The new Legion ==\n=== Second Legion ===\n[[File:Marie Alphonse Bedeau (1804 \u2013 1863).jpg|thumb|upright|Portrait of Marie Alphonse Bedeau.]]\n\nThe departure of the Legion to the Spanish Army in 1835 left a void. Foreigners remained numerous in France, which also needed as many men as possible in Africa and Spain. Accordingly, a [[2nd Foreign Legion (2LE)|New Legion]] formed in December 1835,{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=16}} with a garrison in Paris of one battalion. On March 22, two general staff headquarters companies were formed, and as of June 26, the battalion was complete. The government, tired of the Spanish adventure, licensed a battalion on August 11, 1836, and sent the Legion to Spain.{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=16}} These were the last reinforcements for the Legionnaires in Spain.\n\nThe government again began to form a Legion in November 1836. On November 21, a new battalion was constituted at [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]. With 1,200 men, it embarked at [[Toulon]] on the ''[[French Navy|Suffren]]'' on December 11,{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=16}} and arrived four days later in Algiers.\n\nRecruitment continued in France, and on September 4, 1837, a second battalion was constituted by royal decree. The two battalions together were the equivalent of a regular infantry regiment.\n\nStarting from Algiers, 1837 was for the French Foreign Legion of Africa a succession of battles ending in the peace accord signed between France and the resistance led by [[Emir Abdelkader]], recognizing in the [[Treaty of Tafna]] the sovereignty of France in certain Algerian regions. Despite the treaty, the peace was relative. The Legion undertook harsh expeditions{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=17}} in the valley of Isser to reduce rebel activity whose troublesome activities reached as far as [[Boufarik]].\n\n=== Battle of Constantine ===\n[[File:La prise de Constantine 1837 par Horace Vernet.jpg|thumb|[[Siege of Constantine]], by [[Horace Vernet]]]]\n\nThe relatively calm situation allowed the elaboration of grand maneuvers. [[Constantine (Algeria)|Constantine]] was the subject of focus. All available troops marched towards Constantine, a stronghold on rocks overlooking the Rhummel, considered invulnerable.\n\nSince the unsuccessful expedition of [[Bertrand Clauzel]] which cost him his position, the fall of the [[Citadel]] was crucial. Battle formations constituted one [[Marching Regiment|Marching]] Legion Battalion, 500 men strong under the orders of a [[Ranks in the French Army|chef de bataillon]] ([[Ranks in the French Army|Commandant-Major]]) [[Marie Alphonse Bedeau]].{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=30}}\n\nThe expedition arrived in [[Constantine (Algeria)|Constantine]] on October 6, 1837, and General [[Charles-Marie Denys de Damr\u00e9mont]], governor of Algiers, began the siege. The expedition was divided into four brigades; the Legion was part of the third brigade. The [[artillery]] of g\u00e9n\u00e9ral [[Sylvain Charles Val\u00e9e]] breached the fortress. On October 13, the men launched an assault. The Legionnaires under Colonel Combes, their former chief, engaged in close quarter hand-to-hand combat, clearing the most important arenas.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|pp=30\u201331}} After three dreadful hours of fighting, the Legion and the other brigades managed to take Constantine during the night.\n\nBedeau was designated \"Commandant du Lieu\" and promoted to [[Ranks in the French Army|Lieutenant-colonel]].\n\n=== Posterity ===\nThe conquest of Algeria resulted in another twenty years of mobilization. Following Constantine, the Legion regrouped in Algiers in 1838, numbering 2,823 men{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=18}} on November 10, 1838. It continued to fight, distinguishing itself at Djidjelli, Medea and Miliana, often victorious at the cost of heavy losses.\n\nThe Legion definitely garrisoned in Algeria and France in 1840. First, owing to the return of the survivors of Spain, and their 10,000 enemies{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=27}} which had left their country after the failure of the Carlist revolution. The structural reform which, by the intermediary royal ordinance of December 30, 1840, doubled the Legion in two Foreign Regiments. The [[1st Foreign Regiment]], directed by colonel Mollenbeck, was formed in Algiers on April 1, 1841. Similarly, the [[2nd Foreign Infantry Regiment]], directed by colonel {{ill|Jean-Fran\u00e7ois de Cari\u00e9s de Senilhes|fr}} was constituted at [[Annaba|B\u00f4ne]] on April 21, 1841. The Legion first garrisoned at [[Sidi Bel Abb\u00e8s]] in 1843, and left 119 years later in 1962.\n\nIn addition to Algeria, the Legion saw other action overseas to advance French colonial interests and completed successful campaigns in Indochina, Madagascar, Morocco, and other territories that eventually became part of the French empire. According to Blanchard, the Legion became part of the colonization \"in the professed name of civilization and racial superiority, at a time of rising nationalism and... rivalries between European powers.\"<ref>Blanchard.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Major (France)]]\n*[[Foreign Legion Pioneers (Pionniers)]]\n*[[List of French Foreign Legion units]]\n*[[History of the 2nd Foreign Regiment]]\n*[[Foreign Legion Command]] \n*[[Marie Louis Henry de Granet-Lacroix de Chabri\u00e8res]]\n*[[Patrice de MacMahon, Duke of Magenta]]\n*[[Fran\u00e7ois Certain Canrobert]]\n*[[Fran\u00e7ois Achille Bazaine]]\n*[[French Foreign Legion Music Band (MLE)]]\n*[[Honneur et Fid\u00e9lit\u00e9]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first=Douglas |last=Porch |title=La L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re 1831-1962 |language=fr |trans-title=The French Foreign Legion 1831-1962 |publisher=Fayard |date=1994 |isbn=978-2213031118 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Pierre |last=Montagnon |title=Histoire de la L\u00e9gion de 1831 \u00e0 nos jours |language=fr |trans-title=History of the Legion from 1831 till present |publisher=Pygmalion |date=1999 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Poirmeur |title=Notre vieille L\u00e9gion |language=fr |trans-title=Our Old Legion |publisher=Berger-Levraut |place=Paris |date=1931 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=George |last=Blond |title=Histoire de la L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re 1831-1981 |language=fr |trans-title=History of the French Foreign Legion 1831-1981 |publisher=Club France Loisir |orig-year=1st pub. Librairie Plon |date=1981 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Jean-Luc |last=Messager |title=La L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re 175 ans d'histoire |language=fr |trans-title=The French Foreign Legion 175 years of History |publisher=EPA Hachette livre |date=2007 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first1=John Robert |last1=Young |first2=Erwan |last2=Bergot |title=La L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re voyage \u00e0 l'int\u00e9rieur d'un corps d'\u00e9lite |language=fr |trans-title=The French Foreign Legion travels to an elite corps |publisher=Robert Laffont S.A |date=1984 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=Raoul |last=Girordet |title=La Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 militaire de 1815 \u00e0 nos jour |language=fr |trans-title=The Military Society from 1815 till present |publisher=Librairie acad\u00e9mique Perin |place=Malsherbe |date=1998 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Dominique |last1=Barjot |last2=Chaline |first2=Jean-Pierre |last3=Encrev\u00e9 |first3=Andr\u00e9 |title=La France au XIXs. 1814-1914 |language=fr |trans-title=France in the XIX century. 1814-1914 |publisher=Presse universitaire de France |place=Paris |date=1995 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Jean-Joseph |last=Julaud |title=L'Histoire de France illustr\u00e9e |language=fr |trans-title=Illustrated History of France |publisher=FIRST |place=Paris |date=2005 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{French Foreign Legion navbox}}\n\n[[Category:French Foreign Legion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Foreign Legion Chinese hat Bastille Day 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Mark of Originality of the actual French Foreign Legion, the utilization of the \"[[Turkish crescent|Chinese Hat]]\" ({{lang-fr|Chapeau Chinois}}) marks the history of this corps along with the [[French Foreign Legion Music Band (MLE)|Music]].]]\n\nThe [[French Foreign Legion]] was established in 1831 with the aim of recruiting foreign nationals into the [[France|French]] military service. The Foreign Legion was deeply rooted in the [[French conquest of Algeria]] and France's colonial expansion. The Legion is distinctive in that all its recruits are volunteers, while other national foreign regiments are conscripts or prisoners of war (although this was not the case for the 1831 Legion).\n\n== Foreign nationals in service of France==\n\n=== Ancien R\u00e9gime ===\n\nThe [[List of French monarchs|French monarchy]] had hired foreign soldiers since before the [[Bourbon Restoration]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Crowdy|first=Terry|title=French Revolutionary Infantry 1789-1802|publisher=|year=|isbn=1-84176-660-7|location=|pages=13 and 16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1346, [[Philip VI of France]] deployed 15,000 Genovese at the [[Battle of Crecy]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The 13th century and 14th century also saw the appearance of [[free company|grand companies of Scots]], Castillans, Savoyards, Swiss, and Dutch soldiers of given chiefs or princes.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nDuring the reign of [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]], the French Army consisted of 20%-30% non-French soldiers. Additionally, Louis XI employed a [[Garde Ecossaise]], and 6000 Swiss in 1480.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=11}}\n\n[[Francis I of France|Francis I]] formed a mostly foreign infantry corps and created the {{ill|Foreign Regiments of the Ancien R\u00e9gime|fr|R\u00e9giments \u00e9trangers au service de l'Ancien R\u00e9gime}}.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n \n[[Image:Jean Duplessi-Bertaux 001.jpg|thumb|right|[[10 August (French Revolution)|Day of August 10, 1792]] ''La Prise des Tuileries'' (The taking of the Tuileries). The red uniforms of the [[Swiss]] are distinct from the other combatants.]]\nDuring the [[Seven Years' War]], France mustered 32 foreign regiments: twelve German units, ten Swiss, seven Irish, two Italian and one Scottish.{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=10}}\n\nFollowing the abolition of the monarchy during the [[French Revolution]], the [[National Legislative Assembly (France)|National Legislative Assembly]] allowed the use of foreign soldiers and created foreign volunteer units, such as the {{ill|Foreign Volunteer Units in Service of France|fr|Unit\u00e9s de volontaires \u00e9trangers au service de la France}}. Afterward, the National Legislative Assembly, in the decree of July 26, 1792, stated that \"If the Allied Kings deploy numerous Armies against the free peoples, it is important for them to admit into their ranks all the men whom a sublime impulse calls to fight for the sacred cause of Liberty.\" Accordingly, the ''L\u00e9gion Franche Etrang\u00e8re'' was created on August 1st. A [[Germanic Legion]], an {{ill|Italian Legion|fr|L\u00e9gion Italique}}, a [[Batavian Legion]], and a [[Polish Legions (Napoleonic period)|Polish Legion]] were formed.{{sfn|Poirmeur|1931|p=12}} During this period of 146,000 available soldiers, 42,000 were not French.{{sfn|Blond|1981|p=25}}\n\n=== Empire ===\n\nThe conquests of the [[First French Empire]] led to great demand for foreign troops, with the proportion of non-French national soldiers reaching record proportions. In Spain, one-sixth of formations were foreign soldiers.{{sfn|Blond|1981|p=25}}\n \nAfter his rise to power, [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]] recruited 4,000 Swiss{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}} and then more than 90,000 in the course of his reign.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} They formed the {{ill|Valaison Battalion|fr|bataillon Valaisan}}, in 1805.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn 1805, Russian and Austrian prisoners composed the {{ill|Regiment of Tour d'Auvergne|fr|R\u00e9giment de La Tour d'Auvergne}} and the {{ill|Regiment of Isembourg|fr|R\u00e9giment d'Isembourg}}.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The two were later renamed the 1st Foreign Regiment and 2nd Foreign Regiment{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} and later dissolved in 1814.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe {{ill|Piedmontese Legion|fr|L\u00e9gion Pi\u00e9montaise}} or ''L\u00e9gion du Midi'', created in 1803, was composed of former French soldiers and recruits from the [[Departments of France#Departments of the Napoleonic Empire in Europe|French departments of Italy]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Napoleon's forces would also include the Spanish Pioneers, the {{ill|Catalonian Regiment|fr|R\u00e9giment de Catalogne}}, the {{ill|Hanoverian Legion|fr|L\u00e9gion hanovrienne}}, the Egyptian [[Mamluks]], and the [[Portuguese Legion (Napoleonic Wars)|Portuguese Legion]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nBetween 1806 and 1814, 60 foreign units were constituted and commanded by 136 generals.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}} A large part of these Europeans were volunteers.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} Conscripts came only from the regions annexed by the Empire.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n \nIt is estimated that of the 400,000 men who crossed the [[Neman]] River towards [[Moscow]] or [[Smolensk]], just 120,000 were actually French.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}} During the [[Hundred Days]], Napoleon assembled eight foreign regiments.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n=== Restoration ===\n\nUnder [[Louis XVIII of France]], 14,000 Swiss soldiers in six regiments and four regiments, composed of [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] and Spanish, constituted the Royal Foreign Legion in 1815.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=12}}\n\n== Creation of the French Foreign Legion ==\n\n=== Causes ===\n\nThe creation of the Foreign Legion was in large part was due to the aftermath following the [[July Revolution]].{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984|p=9}}\n\nFollowing the purge of the army after the [[July Revolution]],{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984|p=9}} Louis Philippe I was in need of a way to occupy those seen as dangerous or restless elements of the regular army, whether French or foreign. The Legion became a depository for those who did not conform to the governing agenda. There was also concern over those seen as foreign insurrectionists and volunteer fighters which had journeyed in the hopes of continuing the [[French Revolution|1789 Revolution]].{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=37}} To the State, they threatened the stability of the kingdom and its economy it became urgent to group and distance them.{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=34}}\n\nIn addition, despite the [[enthusiasm]] showcased by the men in the [[Invasion of Algiers in 1830]], morale was at a low{{sfn|Blond|1981|p=25}} and the war, deemed very unpopular. Louis Philipe I was a pacifist and did not want to weigh the national and military opinion on a costly conquest which would endanger French lives and thus sought to use foreign troops. However, since the Kingdom was reduced, it was not feasible to recruit contingents in occupied lands such as during Napoleon's era. Accordingly, a new sort of troop was required.\n\n=== Creation by Royal Ordinance ===\nThe French Foreign Legion was created by Royal Ordinance on March 9, 1831. The ordinance had nine articles.\n{{verse translation|lang=fr|Louis-Philippe, roi des Fran\u00e7ais, \u00e0 tous pr\u00e9sents et \u00e0 venir salut ;\n\nVu la loi du 9 mars 1831 :\n\nSur le rapport de notre Ministre Secr\u00e9taire d\u2019\u00c9tat au D\u00e9partement de la Guerre : Nous avons ordonn\u00e9 et ordonnons ce qui suit :\n\nArt. 1 - Il sera form\u00e9 une L\u00e9gion compos\u00e9e d\u2019\u00c9trangers. Cette L\u00e9gion prendra la d\u00e9nomination de L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re.\nArt. 2 - Les bataillons de la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re auront la m\u00eame formation que les Bataillons d'infanterie de ligne.\nArt. 3 - Pour la solde, les masses et son administration, la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re sera assimil\u00e9e aux r\u00e9giments fran\u00e7ais. L'uniforme sera bleu avec le simple passepoil garance et le pantalon de m\u00eame couleur, les boutons seront jaunes et porteront les mots L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re.\nArt. 4 - Tout \u00c9tranger qui voudra faire partie de la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re ne pourra y \u00eatre admis qu'apr\u00e8s avoir contract\u00e9, devant un sous-intendant militaire, un engagement volontaire.\nArt. 5 - La dur\u00e9e de l'engagement sera de trois ans au moins et de cinq ans au plus.\nArt. 6 - Pour \u00eatre re\u00e7us \u00e0 s'engager, les \u00c9tranger devront n'avoir pas plus de quarante ans, et avoir au moins dix-huit ans accomplis, et la taille de 1m55. Ils devront en outre \u00eatre porteur d'un certificat d'acceptation de l'autorit\u00e9 militaire constatant qu'ils ont les qualit\u00e9s requises pour faire un bon service.\nArt. 7 - En l'absence de pi\u00e8ces, l\u2019\u00c9tranger sera envoy\u00e9 devant l'Officier G\u00e9n\u00e9ral qui d\u00e9cidera si l'engagement peut \u00eatre re\u00e7u.\nArt. 8 - Les militaires faisant partie de la L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re se pourront rengager pour deux ans au moins et cinq ans au plus. Les rengagements ne donneront droit \u00e0 une haute paie qu'autant que les militaires auront accompli cinq ans de service.\nArt. 9 - Notre Ministre Secr\u00e9taire d\u2019\u00c9tat au D\u00e9partement de la Guerre est charg\u00e9 de l'ex\u00e9cution de la pr\u00e9sente ordonnance. Par le Roi :\n\nLe Ministre Secr\u00e9taire d\u2019\u00c9tat de la Guerre Sign\u00e9 : Mar\u00e9chal SOULT Duc de Dalmatie\nsign\u00e9 : LOUIS-PHILIPPE\n|Louis-Philippe, King of the French, to all present and to those to come greetings;\n\nLaw decree of March 9, 1831:\n\nOn the report of our State Minister Secretary at the Ministry of War: We have ordained and we order as follows:\n\nArt. 1 - A Legion will be formed and composed of foreigners. This Legion will be known as the French Foreign Legion.\nArt. 2 - The battalions of the French Foreign Legion will have the same formation as the line infantry battalions.\nArt. 3 - For pay, masses and administration, the French Foreign Legion will be assimilated to French regiments. The uniform will be blue with simple ''passepoil garance'' and pants of the same color, the buttons will be yellow and inscribed with the words ''L\u00e9gion \u00c9trang\u00e8re''.\nArt. 4 - Every foreigner who wishes to be part of the French Foreign Legion, will only be admitted after having contracted, in front of a deputy superintendent, a volunteer enlistment.\nArt. 5 - The duration of the contract of enlistment will be at least three years or a maximum of five years.\nArt. 6 - To enlist, foreigners should not be more than forty and should be at least eighteen years old, with a minimum height of 1m55. They should be attested by and in possession of an acceptance certificate from the competent military authority, who asserts that they have the appropriate qualities for good and proper service.\nArt. 7 - In absence of credentials, the foreigner will be sent to the general officer, who will decide whether his engagement would be acceptable.\nArt. 8 - Military personnel of the French Foreign Legion can reenlist for a period of two and a maximum of five years. High pay is rightly warranted upon accomplishing five years of service.\nArt. 9 - Our State Secretary Minister to the Ministry of War is charged with executing this present ordinance. \n\nThe State Secretary War Minister Signed: Marshal SOULT, Duke of Dalmatia\nsigned: LOUIS-PHILIPE\n}}\n\n=== A challenging start ===\n[[File:Une compagnie de la 2e legion sur les champs de mars.jpg|thumb|A company of the [[2nd Foreign Legion (2LE)|Legion]] on the [[Champ de Mars]] in Paris (1836).]]\n\nThe Legion was formed around former Swiss regiments and the [[Hohenlohe Regiment|Hohenloe regiment]], who formed a nucleus of professional soldiers, however, the experience of recruits varied greatly. To the State, the Legion succeeded in diminishing the number of foreign exiled politicians and potential revolutionaries. It attracted both French and foreign nationals from all walks of life.{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=38}} Certain persons enlisted from a nonetheless motivated allure and voluntary spirit, the times helping and Africa still unknown, so adventurers also enlisted.{{sfn|Blond|1981}} Also, many friends of France, who were numerous, hoped to battle for the nation. Nevertheless, this created a motley corps, where soldiers rubbed elbows with anarchists. Inactivity in wait for assignments and [[nationalism]] of some, entailed high energies between communities, which entailed the need to have a more concise common frame.\n\nOfficers and [[non-commissioned officer]]s were needed;{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=39}} but those of the Imperial Army were too old already and unequal to the times. Foreign officers who had left their armies were not familiar with the [[French language]], and hailed from different armies or other branches of the military. Punishments were numerous and harsh with insubordination and desertion being common. In mid-May, the National Guard was called upon to prevent a possible rebellion. On that day, 20 soldiers were arrested.{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=44}}\n\nDespite these complications, less than six months after the royal ordinance,{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984|p=10}} five battalions were created, each with eight combat companies.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" align='center'\n|+ Nationalities by battalion \n!  !! nationalities\n|-\n| 1st || Swiss and former of Hohenlohe\n|-\n| 2nd || Swiss and Germans \n|-\n| 3rd || Swiss and Germans \n|-\n| 4th || Spanish\n|-\n| 5th || Sardinians and Italians\n|-\n| 6th || Belgians and Dutch \n|}\n\n=== The beginnings ===\n\nStarting the month of August, the 1st, 2nd, 3rd and 5th battalions deployed to Algeria, counting a total of 78 Officers and 2,669 [[Non-commissioned officer|Sous-officiers]] and Legionnaires.{{sfn|Montagnon1999|p=15}}\n\nThe Legion was first preoccupied with [[Fortification|earthworks]] and accordingly gained their reputation as a {{ill|builder soldiers|fr|soldat b\u00e2tisseur}}, the essence base of the Legion. Accordingly, the Legion would build the route of Casbah in the region of Algiers, that of the {{ill|Emperor's Fort|fr|Fort de l'Empereur}}, or that of the belt of Algiers. The Legion also participated in the construction of many [[Forts]], including the Water Fort. During the construction of the works fevers, [[dysentery]] and [[cholera]] would kill or reform 3,200 men between 1831 and 1835).{{sfn|Porch|1994|p=50}}\n\n=== Baptism by fire ===\n\nApril 27, 1832, 300 men of the 3rd battalion began to secure the surrounding of Algiers and engaged in combat at Maison Carr\u00e9. On May 23, a detachment was exterminated: resulting in 26 fatalities.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=16}} The conquest of Algeria cost the French Foreign Legion: 27 Officers, 61 Sous-officiers and 756 Legionnaires.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=19}} Colonel Combes, arrived from [[Marseille]] with the first flag of the Legion offered by [[Ferdinand Philippe, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]], in the name of the [[List of French monarchs|King]].\n\nInscribed on the flag was: ''Le Roi des Fran\u00e7ais \u00e0 la L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re'' (\"King of the French in the French Foreign Legion\"). The troop was then known and distinguished.{{sfn|Messager|2007|pp=222\u2013223}}\n\nThe Legion fought at Sidi Chabal in November 1832, where the Spanish battalion distinguished itself. In March 1833, Legionnaires fought at Ouled Yacoub and Oule Attia, against [[Emir]] [[Emir Abdelkader|Abdelkader]] and the tribes of the [[Sig, Algeria|Sig]].\n\nThe Legion won a victory at [[Arzew]] on June 5 and took [[Mostaganem]] on July 27, 1833.\n\n1835 was marked by fighting at [[Battle of Macta|Moulay Ismael]] and cost the lives of a hundred Legionnaires.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=18}}\n\n== Spain and the end of the old Legion ==\n\n=== Goodwill to Spain ===\n{{See also|Carlism|First Carlist War}}\nOn June 28, 1843, the ambassadors of London, Lisbon, and Paris signed a treaty with Spain supporting Marie-Christina. France did not favor this treaty, because it did not want to interfere in Spanish affairs or risk compromising European peace,{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=21}} and so did not want to send the regular French Army. Sending the Foreign Legion allowed France to justify involvement.\n\nOn January 28, 1835, under pressure from [[Adolphe Thiers]], Minister of Interior, the Legion was ceded to the Queen of Spain. On June 29, a royal ordinance stipulated that the French Foreign Legion was no longer part of the French Army.{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=20}} The [[Army Corps]] had been ceded to Spain, and all Legionnaires embarked: the sick, imprisoned, and those on leave included. The men could not back out or they would face severe sanctions for insubordination.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=21}}\n\nOn July 30, 123 officers and 4,021 [[Non-commissioned officers|Sous-Officiers]] and Legionnaires embarked on [[French Navy|La Royal]]<ref>This was the traditional surname of the [[French Navy|French War Navy]].</ref> heading to Algeria.\n\nDuring a stopover at the [[Balearic Islands]], the battalions were reorganized, and all nationalities mixed together.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=22}}\n\n=== The fighting ===\n\nThe Legion in Spain became the French Auxiliary Division and their chief, colonel Bernelle, became [[Mar\u00e9chal de camp]] of the Spanish Armies. On arrival, the Legion entered the war against 5,000 Carlists in Catalonia. After several skirmishes in Navarre and Aragon, the Legion entered [[Pamplona]] on February 5, 1836 to encircle and isolate the province.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}} \n\nThe Legion often fought alone becoming more autonomous;{{sfn|Young|Bergot|1984}} Bernelle supplemented his troops with three squadrons of lancers, a [[Howitzer]] battery for support, and a [[Company (military unit)|medical]] company. This was the beginning of the modern French Foreign Legion.\n\nDay after day, the Legion lost men. On April 15, 1836, losses had risen to 117 killed, 380 dead of wounds or disease, and 83 deserters.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999}} At Tirapequi on April 26, 500 Legionnaires repelled 3,500 Carlists at the cost of 90 dead{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}} and, on August 1, at [[Zubiri, Navarre|Zubiri]], the Legion all alone killed 1,200 Carlists in one battle.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}}\n\n=== The Legion abandoned ===\n\nIn Spain, the Legion became more and more isolated with reinforcements arriving sporadically.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=24}} Paris turned a deaf ear, equipment and supplies were insufficient, the pay was irregular, and decorations and advancement did not follow. [[Adolphe Thiers]], president of the council, refused them aid, saying that the Legion had been handed in full and entirely to Spain. Reaching a limit, Bernelle resigned and returned to France. The King didn't want to send reinforcements from the [[French Army|regular army]], out of fear of tiring the troops and becoming entrenched. In addition, the conquest of Algeria required reinforcements. The King did not want to divide his troops. The Legion was accordingly left to its fate.\n\n=== Misery and wandering ===\n\nThe Legion continued to fight, the lack of decent equipment aggravated by the particularly bitter winter of 1836-1837 in the plains of [[Aragon]]. With their pay in default and their living conditions poor, some joined the Carlists who were living off the land.\n\nAt the beginning of 1837, the Legion had only three battalions, then two; the Legion had been reduced in half since its arrival. However, the Legion continued to fight with a suicidal determination.{{sfn|Poirmeur|1931|p=26}}\n\nIn 1838, the Legion was a shadow of itself in poor living conditions, without resources, and surrounded by Carlists. It was not until December 8 that the Queen finally granted its dissolution. They left Zaragoza on January 2, 1839 and crossed the Pyrenees, starved and miserable. \n \nSome 6,000 had disembarked at Tarragona in 1835, but only 63 Officers and 50 troops returned.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=26}} During the Spanish odyssey, the King had created [[2nd Foreign Legion (2LE)|another Legion]].\n\n== The new Legion ==\n\n=== Second Legion ===\n[[File:Marie Alphonse Bedeau (1804 \u2013 1863).jpg|thumb|upright|Portrait of Marie Alphonse Bedeau.]]\n\nThe departure of the Legion to the Spanish Army in 1835 left a void. Foreigners remained numerous in France, which also needed as many men as possible in Africa and Spain. Accordingly, a [[2nd Foreign Legion (2LE)|New Legion]] formed in December 1835,{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=16}} with a garrison in Paris of one battalion. On March 22, two general staff headquarters companies were formed, and as of June 26, the battalion was complete. The government, tired of the Spanish adventure, licensed a battalion on August 11, 1836, and sent the Legion to Spain.{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=16}} These were the last reinforcements for the Legionnaires in Spain.\n\nThe government again began to form a Legion in November 1836. On November 21, a new battalion was constituted at [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]. With 1,200 men, it embarked at [[Toulon]] on the ''[[French Navy|Suffren]]'' on December 11,{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=16}} and arrived four days later in Algiers.\n\nRecruitment continued in France, and on September 4, 1837, a second battalion was constituted by royal decree. The two battalions together were the equivalent of a regular infantry regiment.\n\nStarting from Algiers, 1837 was for the French Foreign Legion of Africa a succession of battles ending in the peace accord signed between France and the resistance led by [[Emir Abdelkader]], recognizing in the [[Treaty of Tafna]] the sovereignty of France in certain Algerian regions. Despite the treaty, the peace was relative. The Legion undertook harsh expeditions{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=17}} in the valley of Isser to reduce rebel activity whose troublesome activities reached as far as [[Boufarik]].\n\n=== Battle of Constantine ===\n[[File:La prise de Constantine 1837 par Horace Vernet.jpg|thumb|[[Siege of Constantine]], by [[Horace Vernet]]]]\n\nThe relatively calm situation allowed the elaboration of grand maneuvers. [[Constantine (Algeria)|Constantine]] was the subject of focus. All available troops marched towards Constantine, a stronghold on rocks overlooking the Rhummel, considered invulnerable.\n\nSince the unsuccessful expedition of [[Bertrand Clauzel]] which cost him his position, the fall of the [[Citadel]] was crucial. Battle formations constituted one [[Marching Regiment|Marching]] Legion Battalion, 500 men strong under the orders of a [[Ranks in the French Army|chef de bataillon]] ([[Ranks in the French Army|Commandant-Major]]) [[Marie Alphonse Bedeau]].{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=30}}\n\nThe expedition arrived in [[Constantine (Algeria)|Constantine]] on October 6, 1837, and General [[Charles-Marie Denys de Damr\u00e9mont]], governor of Algiers, began the siege. The expedition was divided into four brigades; the Legion was part of the third brigade. The [[artillery]] of g\u00e9n\u00e9ral [[Sylvain Charles Val\u00e9e]] breached the fortress. On October 13, the men launched an assault. The Legionnaires under Colonel Combes, their former chief, engaged in close quarter hand-to-hand combat, clearing the most important arenas.{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|pp=30\u201331}} After three dreadful hours of fighting, the Legion and the other brigades managed to take Constantine during the night.\n\nBedeau was designated \"Commandant du Lieu\" and promoted to [[Ranks in the French Army|Lieutenant-colonel]].\n\n=== Posterity ===\n\nThe conquest of Algeria resulted in another twenty years of mobilization. Following Constantine, the Legion regrouped in Algiers in 1838, numbering 2,823 men{{sfn|Messager|2007|p=18}} on November 10, 1838. It continued to fight, distinguishing itself at Djidjelli, Medea and Miliana, often victorious at the cost of heavy losses.\n\nThe Legion definitely garrisoned in Algeria and France in 1840. First, owing to the return of the survivors of Spain, and their 10,000 enemies{{sfn|Montagnon|1999|p=27}} which had left their country after the failure of the Carlist revolution. The structural reform which, by the intermediary royal ordinance of December 30, 1840, doubled the Legion in two Foreign Regiments. The [[1st Foreign Regiment]], directed by colonel Mollenbeck, was formed in Algiers on April 1, 1841. Similarly, the [[2nd Foreign Infantry Regiment]], directed by colonel {{ill|Jean-Fran\u00e7ois de Cari\u00e9s de Senilhes|fr}} was constituted at [[Annaba|B\u00f4ne]] on April 21, 1841. The Legion first garrisoned at [[Sidi Bel Abb\u00e8s]] in 1843, and left 119 years later in 1962.\n\nIn addition to Algeria, the Legion saw other action overseas to advance French colonial interests and completed successful campaigns in Indochina, Madagascar, Morocco, and other territories that eventually became part of the French empire. According to Blanchard, the Legion became part of the colonization \"in the professed name of civilization and racial superiority, at a time of rising nationalism and... rivalries between European powers.\"<ref>Blanchard.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Major (France)]]\n*[[Foreign Legion Pioneers (Pionniers)]]\n*[[List of French Foreign Legion units]]\n*[[History of the 2nd Foreign Regiment]]\n*[[Foreign Legion Command]] \n*[[Marie Louis Henry de Granet-Lacroix de Chabri\u00e8res]]\n*[[Patrice de MacMahon, Duke of Magenta]]\n*[[Fran\u00e7ois Certain Canrobert]]\n*[[Fran\u00e7ois Achille Bazaine]]\n*[[French Foreign Legion Music Band (MLE)]]\n*[[Honneur et Fid\u00e9lit\u00e9]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first=Douglas |last=Porch |title=La L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re 1831-1962 |language=fr |trans-title=The French Foreign Legion 1831-1962 |publisher=Fayard |date=1994 |isbn=978-2213031118 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Pierre |last=Montagnon |title=Histoire de la L\u00e9gion de 1831 \u00e0 nos jours |language=fr |trans-title=History of the Legion from 1831 till present |publisher=Pygmalion |date=1999 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Poirmeur |title=Notre vieille L\u00e9gion |language=fr |trans-title=Our Old Legion |publisher=Berger-Levraut |place=Paris |date=1931 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=George |last=Blond |title=Histoire de la L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re 1831-1981 |language=fr |trans-title=History of the French Foreign Legion 1831-1981 |publisher=Club France Loisir |orig-year=1st pub. Librairie Plon |date=1981 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Jean-Luc |last=Messager |title=La L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re 175 ans d'histoire |language=fr |trans-title=The French Foreign Legion 175 years of History |publisher=EPA Hachette livre |date=2007 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first1=John Robert |last1=Young |first2=Erwan |last2=Bergot |title=La L\u00e9gion \u00e9trang\u00e8re voyage \u00e0 l'int\u00e9rieur d'un corps d'\u00e9lite |language=fr |trans-title=The French Foreign Legion travels to an elite corps |publisher=Robert Laffont S.A |date=1984 |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book |first=Raoul |last=Girordet |title=La Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 militaire de 1815 \u00e0 nos jour |language=fr |trans-title=The Military Society from 1815 till present |publisher=Librairie acad\u00e9mique Perin |place=Malsherbe |date=1998 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Dominique |last1=Barjot |last2=Chaline |first2=Jean-Pierre |last3=Encrev\u00e9 |