n Thailand and 308th in world rankings in 2017, considered by alumni, researches, quality of curriculums and instructors.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* In the [[Round University Ranking]] 2017. Chulalongkorn is ranked the 1st in Thailand and ranked 398th in the world.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* In the RUR Research Performance World University Rankings 2016. Chulalongkorn is No. 1 university in Thailand and No. 424 in the world\n* In the CWTS Leiden Ranking 2016. Chulalongkorn is ranked the first in Thailand and 432nd in the world.<ref name=\":4\" />\n* In the THE World University Rankings 2016. Chulalongkorn is ranked 601\u2013800 in the world.<ref name=\":5\" />\n* In the RUR Reputation Rankings 2016. Chulalongkorn is No. 1 university in Thailand and No. 182 in the world.<ref name=\":12\" />\n* In the SCImago institutions Ranking, which ranks international researches of universities. Chulalongkorn is ranked 475th in World rankings in 2016, up six places from last year.<ref name=\":6\" />\n* In the Academic Ranking of World Universities 2017. Chulalongkorn is No. 1 university in Thailand and No. 401-500 in the world.<ref name=\":14\" />\n* In the Nature Index, the affiliations of high-quality scientific articles. Chulalongkorn is ranked the 1st in Thailand in 2016.<ref name=\":7\" />\n* ''US News'' ranked Chulalongkorn 522th in the world.<ref name=\":8\" /> based on the university's reputation, medium, citations, international cooperation, and he quantity of PhD students.\n*In the ''2018 Times Higher Education Emerging Economies Index'', Chula ranked 126.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/news/general/1461965/chula-falls-to-126th-in-times-uni-ranking|title=Chula falls to 126th in Times uni ranking|date=10 May 2018|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-11-05}}</ref>  \n* '''QS World University Ranking by Subject 2018'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chula.ac.th/en/archive/6593|title=CU Subjects Top Country's List in QS World University Ranking by Subject 2017|access-date=2017-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/chulalongkorn-university/undergrad|title=Chulalongkorn University|date=2012-12-06|work=Top Universities|access-date=2018-03-06|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!World rank\n!Subject\n|-\n!'''48''' \n|\n* Mineral & Mining Engineering\n|-\n!'''51 \u2013 100''' \n|\n* Chemical Engineering\n|-\n!'''101 \u2013 150'''\n|\n* Accounting & Finance\n* Architecture / Built Environment\n* Environmental Sciences\n* Geography\n* Modern Languages  \n* Pharmacy & Pharmacology \n* Politics & International Studies \n|-\n!'''151 \u2013 200'''\n|\n* Business & Management Studies \n* Chemistry\n* Civil & Structural Engineering \n* Electrical & Electronic Engineering \n* Linguistics\n* Materials Science\n* Mechanical, Aeronautical & Manufacturing Engineering\n* Medicine\n* Sociology  \n|-\n!'''201 \u2013 250'''\n|\n* Biological Sciences\n* Computer Science & Information Systems \n* Economics & Econometrics \n|-\n!'''301 \u2013 350'''\n|\n* Physics & Astronomy\n|}\n'''Other Rankings'''\n* In the UI Green Metric-City Center, Chulalongkorn was ranked the 1st in national rankings and the 15th in world rankings.<ref name=\":9\" /> considered by Setting and Infrastructure, Energy and Climate Change, Waste, Water, Transportation and Education.\n* The Webometric ranking  indicates quantity and quality of the university's medium, considered by being searched by search engines, online documents, and citations in Google Scholar.  Chulalongkorn is ranked the 1st in national rankings 548th in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.webometrics.info/en/Asia/Thailand|title=Thailand {{!}} Ranking Web of Universities|website=webometrics.info|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n\n== Scholarships ==\n=== Research scholarships ===\n* The 90th Anniversary of Chulalongkorn University Scholarship\n* CU.Graduate School Thesis Grant\n* Overseas Research Experience Scholarship for Graduate Student\n* Overseas Academic Presentation Scholarship for Graduate Students\n* Overseas Academic Presentation Scholarship Option II  for Graduate Student's and Postdoctoral Fellow's Publication\n* Domestic Academic Presentation Scholarship for  Graduate Student\n* Postdoctoral Fellowship\n\n=== Education scholarships ===\n* The  100th Anniversary Chulalongkorn University for Doctoral Scholarship\n* H.M. King Bhumibhol Adulyadej's 72nd Birthday Anniversary Scholarship\n* Thainess Study Scholarship for Graduate Students\n* 60/40 Support for Tuition Fee \n* Teaching  Assistant Scholarship\n* Research Assistant Scholarship     \n* Tuition fees Scholarship for Master to Doctoral \n* ASEAN Scholarship\n* Scholarship for International Graduate Students\n\n==Campus==\n===Chulalongkorn Centenary Park===\nThe west side of Chula's campus is the site of this innovative park. It has gradually sloping portions.<ref>https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/a-secret-weapon-from-thailand-that-can-change-the-future-of-mumbai/thailands-secret-weapon/slideshow/74438975.cms</ref> Its 28 [[Rai (unit)|rai]] expanse contains a water retention pond with a capacity of 3.8 million liters and a rain garden. Both help to ameliorate Bangkok's seasonal flooding. It was built to commemorate Chula's 100th anniversary in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ocharoenchai |first1=Nanticha |title=Seeing green is believing |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/lifestyle/social-and-lifestyle/1578442/seeing-green-is-believing |accessdate=20 November 2018 |work=Bangkok Post |date=19 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Accommodation ===\nChulalongkorn University International House (CU iHouse)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pmcu.co.th/?page_id=9795|title=CU iHOUSE|website=PMCU|language=th|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> is a 26-storey, 846-unit, on campus residence for international students and lecturers. Rooms come fully furnished with air conditioning, modern conveniences, 24-hour security and safety systems. The residence is included in the university's shuttle bus services.\n\n== Honorary degrees ==\nThe university has bestowed honorary degrees on heads of state and other international dignitaries, including two U.S. presidents:\n*[[Lyndon B. Johnson]], October 29, 1966<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://th.usembassy.gov/potus-visit-02/|title=President Johnson received an Honorary Doctorate in Political Science from Chulalongkorn University. {{!}} U.S. Embassy & Consulate in Thailand|newspaper=U.S. Embassy & Consulate in Thailand|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref>\n*[[Bill Clinton]], November 26, 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=52284|title=William J. Clinton: Remarks at Chulalongkorn University in Bangkok|website=presidency.ucsb.edu|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson Mandela]], July 17, 1997<ref>{{cite web|url=http://db.nelsonmandela.org/tributes/pub_view.asp?pg=results&opt=guided&strGenre=Honorary |title=Nelson Mandela Centre of Memory |publisher=Db.nelsonmandela.org |date= |accessdate=2013-05-20}}</ref>\n\n== Traditions ==\nChulalongkorn University student traditions include:\n* [[Chula\u2013Thammasat Traditional Football Match]]: The annual [[association football|football]] match between Chulalongkorn University and [[Thammasat University]] in January at [[Suphashalasai Stadium]]. It first started in 1934.\n* [[Loy Krathong]]: an annual celebration of the full moon night, which usually falls on the first full moon day in November. Since the festival is open to the public, it attracts many people, especially Chulalongkorn students and faculty and those who live in downtown Bangkok, to come to the university to float their krathongs on the university's pond.\n* Chulalongkorn Academic Exhibition: a triennial academic and research exhibition presented by Chulalongkorn University's students and faculty. It is regarded as one of the most important academic fairs in Thailand.\n\n== Student activities and clubs ==\n[[File:\u0e2b\u0e2d\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e01\u0e19\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e15-CUDorm.jpg|thumb|271x271px|Chulalongkorn University dormitory]]\n\nThe university is host to 40 student clubs, including the Buddhism and Traditions Club, the Religious Studies Club, the Mind Study Club, and the Thai Classical Music Club. Chulalongkorn also has a Morals Network, which actively campaigns to protect student activities from damaging the university's reputation. The university's Cheer Club annually organizes the Chula-Thammasat traditional football match.\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{refimprove section|date=January 2012}}\n{{Main|List of Chulalongkorn University people}}\n{{multiple image | perrow = 2\n| image1 = chit.jpg\n| width1 = 100\n|caption1=[[Chit Phumisak]]\n\n| image2 = Surakiart Sathirathai 20050915.jpg\n| width2 = 90\n|caption2=[[Surakiart Sathirathai]]\n\n| image3=MVCun1979.jpg\n| width3 = 95\n|caption3 = [[Mallica Vajrathon]]\n\n| image4 = Banjong Pisanthanakun at MTV Onair Live.jpg\n| width4 = 98\n|caption4 = [[Banjong Pisanthanakun]]\n}}[[File:Prof.Yong.jpg|200px|thumb|[[Yong Poovorawan]]]]\n* [[Mahidol Adulyadej|Prince Mahidol Adulyadej of Songkhla]], father of [[Ananda Mahidol|King Ananda Mahidol]] and [[Bhumibol Adulyadej|King Bhumibol Adulyadej]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/news/centennial-prince-mahidol/|title=Thailand's \"Father of Modern Medicine\"|date=2014-01-23|work=News|access-date=2017-09-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>Becker, William H. Innovative Partners The Rockefeller Foundation and Thailand. New York, New York: The Rockefeller Foundation, 2013. William H. Becker. \u201cAssets: Rockefellerfoundation.\u201d Rockefellerfoundation. 2013. https://assets.rockefellerfoundation.org/app/uploads/20131001203515/Innovative-Partners.pdf (29 November 2016 accessed).</ref>\n* [[Galyani Vadhana|Princess Galyani Vadhana]], princess of [[Narathiwat Province|Narathiwat]], Thailand\n* [[Maha Chakri Sirindhorn|Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn]], princess of Thailand\n* [[Siriwannawari Nariratana|Princess Sirivannavari Nariratana]], princess of Thailand\n* [[Banjong Pisanthanakun]], co-directed and co-written of a box-office hit film such as ''[[Shutter (2004 film)|Shutter]]'' (which was re-made in the US as ''[[Shutter (2008 film)|Shutter]]'', and in [[India]] as ''[[Sivi (film)|Sivi]]'' and ''[[Alone (2007 film)|Alone]]'')\n* [[Surakiart Sathirathai]], former Deputy Prime Minister of [[Thailand]] Foreign Affairs, Education and Culture and the former Thailand's candidate for [[United Nations]] [[United Nations Secretary-General|Secretary-General]] in 2006\n* [[Mallica Vajrathon]], a sociologist, political scientist and former United Nations Senior Staff member\n* [[Win Lyovarin]], a Thai writer, two-time winner of the [[S.E.A. Write Award]]\n* [[Binlah Sonkalagiri]], a winner of the [[S.E.A. Write Award]]\n* [[Thanpuying Dhasanawalaya Sornsongkram]], daughter of Princess Galyani Vadhana\n* [[Apinan Poshyananda]], Director-General, Office of Contemporary Art, The Ministry of Culture and one of the top curators in the Asian region\n* [[Pinyo Suwankiri]], Thailand National Artist in the area of applied arts (Thai architecture)\n* [[Borwornsak Uwanno]], a Thai legal expert and a cabinet secretary-general under the Thaksin-government\n* [[Tawan Vihokratana]], Thai actor and model\n* [[Thitipoom Techaapaikhun]], Thai actor<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7PhPtIYy5go</ref>\n* [[Kiatisuk Senamuang]], a professional football player\n* [[Sukhumbhand Paribatra]], the 15th Governor of Bangkok\n*[[Suporn Watanyusakul]], pioneer in vaginoplasty & facial reconstruction\n* [[Pakorn Chatborirak]], Thai actor and model.\n* [[Yong Poovorawan]], a noted scientist in the fields of pediatric hepatology, [[viral hepatitis]] and [[virology]], and an expert on the [[H5N1]] [[avian influenza]] virus\n*[[Chit Phumisak]], a [[Thailand|Thai]] author, [[philology|philologist]], historian, poet and Communist rebel. His most influential book was ''The Face of Thai Feudalism'' ({{Lang-th|\u0e42\u0e09\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e49\u0e32\u0e28\u0e31\u0e01\u0e14\u0e34\u0e19\u0e32\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22}}, ''Chom Na Sakdina Thai''). He also has been described as the \"[[Che Guevara|Che]] of Thailand\".\n* [[Alexander Rendell]], Thai actor and model.\n* [[Natapohn Tameeruks]], Thai actor and model.\n* [[Urassaya Sperbund]], Thai actor and model.\n* [[Pachara Chirathivat]], Thai actor\n* [[Chantavit Dhanasevi]], Thai actor\n\n== International reputation ==\n* Two medals from Olympic 2016 Rio de Janeiro games\n** [[Tawin Hanprab]], Silver medal, Men's \u221258&nbsp;kg taekwondo.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sa.chula.ac.th/announcement/%E0%B8%AA%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%AA%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%88%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%AC%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%AF-%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%B1%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%AC%E0%B8%B2%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%97/|title=\u0e2a\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e19\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e15\u0e08\u0e38\u0e2c\u0e32\u0e2f \u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e01\u0e35\u0e2c\u0e32\u0e40\u0e17\u0e04\u0e27\u0e31\u0e19\u0e42\u0e14\u0e17\u0e35\u0e21\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e15\u0e34\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22 \u0e04\u0e27\u0e49\u0e32\u0e21\u0e32\u0e44\u0e14\u0e49 2 \u0e40\u0e2b\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e0d\u0e08\u0e32\u0e01\u0e01\u0e35\u0e2c\u0e32\u0e42\u0e2d\u0e25\u0e34\u0e21\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e01 2016|last=\u0e08\u0e38\u0e2c\u0e32\u0e25\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e4c\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22|website=\u0e2a\u0e33\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e23\u0e01\u0e34\u0e08\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e19\u0e34\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e15|language=th|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/learning/advanced/1064829/olympics-tawin-wins-silver-panipak-wins-bronze-ariya-tops-day-1-golf|title=Olympics: Tawin wins silver, Panipak wins bronze, Ariya tops day 1 golf|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref>\n** [[Panipak Wongpattanakit]], Bronze medal, Women's \u221249&nbsp;kg taekwondo.<ref name=\":11\" />\n* The [https://compete.imagine.microsoft.com/en-us/team/105016 PH21] team, Computer Engineering students at Chulalongkorn University, got the 1st prize from the Microsoft Imagine Cup 2016 in the games category<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.microsoft.com/firehose/2016/07/28/category-winners-announced-in-microsoft-imagine-cup-setting-stage-for-fridays-world-championship/#sm.000fk5alo12p7eo5rcg16qxniuetc|title=Games, Innovation and World Citizenship winners announced in Microsoft Imagine Cup, setting stage for Friday's World Championship - The Fire Hose|date=2016-07-28|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-18}}</ref>\n* Chulalongkorn University Concert Choir Won Gold Award in World-Class Musical Competition 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chula.ac.th/en/archive/2794|title=Chulalongkorn University Concert Choir Won Gold Award in World-Class Musical Competition|access-date=2016-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/microsoftimagine/2016/10/27/this-imagine-cup-team-gives-you-the-power-to-manipulate-time-and-see-the-future/|title=This Imagine Cup team gives you the power to manipulate time and see the future|newspaper=Microsoft Imagine Blog|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Robocup competitions ===\nThe university [[RoboCup]] team, '''Plasma\u2010Z''', got several prizes from the robotics competition as follow.<ref>[http://kucitypic.kasetsart.org/kucity.com8/kucity8_robocup2009_Symposium/tdps/small/small_plasma_z.pdf PlasmaZ Extended Team Description Paper]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*In 2005, almost reached the quarter-final at [[Osaka]] RoboCup.\n*In 2006, the third place and technical challenge at [[Bremen]] RoboCup.\n*In 2007, second place [[Atlanta]] World RoboCup.\n*In 2008, finally, the team got champion of World RoboCup Small\u2010Sized Robot League at [[Suzhou]], [[China]].\nMoreover, another university Robocup team, '''Plasma-RX''' has participated in Rescue robot league at World RoboCup 2008, Suzhou, China, and won the first prize and the best-in-class in mobility award.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=|doi=10.1109/ROBIO.2009.4913305|isbn=978-1-4244-2678-2|chapter=Plasma-RX: Autonomous Rescue robots|title=2008 IEEE International Conference on Robotics and Biomimetics|year=2009|last1=Chuengsatiansup|first1=K.|last2=Sajjapongse|first2=K.|last3=Kruapraditsiri|first3=P.|last4=Chanma|first4=C.|last5=Termthanasombat|first5=N.|last6=Suttasupa|first6=Y.|last7=Sattaratnamai|first7=S.|last8=Pongkaew|first8=E.|last9=Udsatid|first9=P.|last10=Hattha|first10=B.|last11=Wibulpolprasert|first11=P.|last12=Usaphapanus|first12=P.|last13=Tulyanon|first13=N.|last14=Wongsaisuwan|first14=M.|last15=Wannasuphoprasit|first15=W.|last16=Chongstitvatana|first16=P.|pages=1986\u20131990}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cp.eng.chula.ac.th/~piak/paper/2009/Plasma-RX19.pdf Plasma-RX: Autonomous Rescue Robots]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Academic dress of Chulalongkorn University]]\n* [[Sasin Graduate Institute of Business Administration of Chulalongkorn University]]\n* [[Education in Thailand]]\n* [[Chula United|Chula United football club]]\n* [https://stat.cbs.chula.ac.th Department of Statistics] | Chulalongkorn Business School\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Chulalongkorn_University}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.chula.ac.th|Chulalongkorn University official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160919043434/http://www.grad.chula.ac.th/eng/ Graduate School, Chulalongkorn University]\n* [http://www.sasin.edu Sasin Graduate Institute of Business Administration of Chulalongkorn University]\n*[https://inter-bascii-chula.com/ School of Integrated Innovation]\n* [http://www.atc.chula.ac.th/en_html/en_tep.html CU-TEP]\n* [http://www.chula.ac.th/CUpano/CUpanoM1/CuPano.html Panoramic view of Chulalongkorn]\n\n\n{{Chulalongkorn University}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Links to related articles\n|list =\n{{Universities in Thailand}}\n{{ASEAN University Network |state=collapsed}}\n{{APRU}}\n{{ASAIHL}}\n|state =autocollapse\n}}\n\n[[Category:Chulalongkorn University| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Education in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1917]]\n[[Category:ASEAN University Network]]\n[[Category:Pathum Wan District]]\n[[Category:Universities in Thailand]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Siam]]\n[[Category:Universities established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to Chulalongkorn]]\n", "name_user": "Xcalibur123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSocial science and humanities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chulalongkorn_University"}
{"title_page": "Angelo Baroni", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix = Most Reverend\n| name        = Angelo Baroni\n| title       =\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| church      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = \n| diocese     = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Chioggia|Diocese of Chioggia]]\n| see         = \n| term        = 1611\u20131612\n| predecessor = [[Raphael Riva]]\n| successor   = [[Bartolomeo Cartolario]]\n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = \n| ordained_by    = \n| consecration   = 22 February 1604\n| consecrated_by = [[Girolamo Bernerio]]\n| cardinal       =\n| rank           = \n<!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date    = 1553\n| birth_place   = [[Venice]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date    = November 1612 (age 59)\n| death_place   = [[Chioggia]], [[Italy]]\n| previous_post = [[Bishop of Kotor]] (1604\u20131611)\n| nationality   = \n}}\n\n'''Angelo Baroni''' (1553 &ndash; November 1612) was a Roman Catholic prelate who served as [[Bishop of Chioggia]] (1611\u20131612) and [[Bishop of Kotor]] (1604\u20131611).\n\n==Biography==\nAngelo Baroni was born in [[Venice]], [[Italy]] and ordained a priest in the [[Order of Preachers]].<ref name=CathHierAngBar>{{cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|title=Bishop Angelo Baroni, O.P. |website=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bbaronia.html |accessdate=June 16, 2018}} [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref><ref name=GCathAngBar>{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Bishop Angelo Baroni, O.P. |publisher=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/chio0.htm#33708 |accessdate=June 16, 2018}} [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref>\nOn 11 February 1604, he was appointed during the papacy of [[Pope Clement VIII]] as [[Bishop of Kotor]].<ref name=CathHierAngBar /> \nOn 22 February 1604, he was consecrated bishop by [[Girolamo Bernerio]], [[Cardinal-Bishop]] of ''Albano'', with [[Agostino Quinzio]], [[Bishop of Kor\u010dula]], and Gregorio Servanzi, [[Bishop of Trevico]], serving as co-consecrators.<ref name=CathHierAngBar /> \nOn 31 August 1611, he was appointed during the papacy of [[Pope Paul V]] as [[Bishop of Chioggia]].<ref name=CathHierAngBar /> He served as Bishop of Chioggia until his death in November 1612.<ref name=CathHierAngBar />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links and additional sources==\n*{{cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|title=Diocese of Kotor (Cattaro) |website=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dkoto.html|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n*{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Diocese of Kotor (Croatia)|publisher=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/koto0.htm|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n*{{cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|title=Diocese of Chioggia |website=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dchgg.html|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n*{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Diocese of Chioggia (Italy)|website=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/chio0.htm|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Bishop of Kotor]]\n| years = 1604\u20131611\n| before = Girolamo Bucchia\n| after = Girolamo Rusca\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Bishop of Chioggia]]\n| years = 1611\u20131612\n| before = [[Raphael Riva]]\n| after = [[Bartolomeo Cartolario]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Italy}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baroni, Angelo}}\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops appointed by Pope Clement VIII]]\n[[Category:Bishops appointed by Pope Paul V]]\n[[Category:1553 births]]\n[[Category:1612 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Italy-RC-bishop-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix = Most Reverend\n| name        = Angelo Baroni\n| title       =\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| church      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = \n| diocese     = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Chioggia|Diocese of Chioggia]]\n| see         = \n| term        = 1611\u20131612\n| predecessor = [[Raphael Riva]]\n| successor   = [[Bartolomeo Cartolario]]\n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = \n| ordained_by    = \n| consecration   = 22 February 1604\n| consecrated_by = [[Girolamo Bernerio]]\n| cardinal       =\n| rank           = \n<!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date    = 1553\n| birth_place   = [[Venice]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date    = November 1612 (age 59)\n| death_place   = [[Chioggia]], [[Italy]]\n| previous_post = [[Bishop of Kotor]] (1604\u20131611)\n| nationality   = \n}}\n\n'''Angelo Baroni''' (1553 &ndash; November 1612) was a Roman Catholic prelate who served as [[Bishop of Chioggia]] (1611\u20131612) and [[Bishop of Kotor]] (1604\u20131611).\n\n==Biography==\nAngelo Baroni was born in [[Venice]], [[Italy]] and ordained a priest in the [[Order of Preachers]].<ref name=CathHierAngBar>{{cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|title=Bishop Angelo Baroni, O.P. |website=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bbaronia.html |accessdate=June 16, 2018}} [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref><ref name=GCathAngBar>{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Bishop Angelo Baroni, O.P. |publisher=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/chio0.htm#33708 |accessdate=June 16, 2018}} [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]</ref>\nOn 11 February 1604, he was appointed during the papacy of [[Pope Clement VIII]] as [[Bishop of Kotor]].<ref name=CathHierAngBar /> \nOn 22 February 1604, he was consecrated bishop by [[Girolamo Bernerio]], [[Cardinal-Bishop]] of ''Albano'', with [[Agostino Quinzio]], [[Bishop of Kor\u010dula]], and [[Gregorio Servanzi]], [[Bishop of Trevico]], serving as co-consecrators.<ref name=CathHierAngBar /> \nOn 31 August 1611, he was appointed during the papacy of [[Pope Paul V]] as [[Bishop of Chioggia]].<ref name=CathHierAngBar /> He served as Bishop of Chioggia until his death in November 1612.<ref name=CathHierAngBar />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links and additional sources==\n*{{cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|title=Diocese of Kotor (Cattaro) |website=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dkoto.html|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n*{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Diocese of Kotor (Croatia)|publisher=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/koto0.htm|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n*{{cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|title=Diocese of Chioggia |website=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dchgg.html|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n*{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Diocese of Chioggia (Italy)|website=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/chio0.htm|accessdate=June 16, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops) [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Bishop of Kotor]]\n| years  = 1604\u20131611\n| before = [[Girolamo Bucchia]]\n| after  = [[Girolamo Rusca]]}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Bishop of Chioggia]]\n| years  = 1611\u20131612\n| before = [[Raphael Riva]]\n| after  = [[Bartolomeo Cartolario]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Italy}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baroni, Angelo}}\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops appointed by Pope Clement VIII]]\n[[Category:Bishops appointed by Pope Paul V]]\n[[Category:1553 births]]\n[[Category:1612 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Italy-RC-bishop-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Podiabaal", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angelo_Baroni"}
